The Institut Geologii Arktiki Rocks (70°56′S11°30′E﻿ / ﻿70.933°S 11.500°E) are a group of scattered rock outcrops that extend in an east–west direction for 20 miles (32 km), located 7 miles (11 km) south of the Schirmacher Hills in Queen Maud Land, [MASK].
Isbrynet Hill (73°9′S4°28′W﻿ / ﻿73.150°S 4.467°W) is a rock hill southwest of Penck Ledge, rising above the ice slopes at the west side of the head of Penck Trough in Queen Maud Land, [MASK].
Ising Glacier (72°24′S0°57′E﻿ / ﻿72.400°S 0.950°E) is a glacier flowing northwest between Isingen Mountain and Kvitkjolen Ridge in the Sverdrup Mountains of Queen Maud Land, [MASK].
Isfossnipa Peak (73°9′S1°30′W﻿ / ﻿73.150°S 1.500°W) is a peak 2 miles (3 km) southeast of Austvorren Ridge, surmounting the eastern part of the Neumayer Cliffs in Queen Maud Land, [MASK].
Istind Peak (72°6′S2°23′W﻿ / ﻿72.100°S 2.383°W) is a partly ice-covered peak 1 mile (1.6 km) south of Tindeklypa, on the east side of Ahlmann Ridge in Queen Maud Land, [MASK].
Istindhalsen Saddle is an ice saddle between Istind Peak and the Grunehogna Peaks in the Ahlmann Ridge of Queen Maud Land, [MASK].

Habermehl Peak (German: Habermehlgipfel, 71°49′S6°55′E﻿ / ﻿71.817°S 6.917°E) is a peak 2,945 metres (9,660 ft) high, 3 miles (5 km) south of Gessner Peak in the northeast part of the Mühlig-Hofmann Mountains of Queen Maud Land, [MASK].

Austranten Rock (71°24′S14°2′E﻿ / ﻿71.400°S 14.033°E) is an isolated rock outcrop lying 2 miles (3 km) southeast of Todt Ridge, at the eastern extremity of the Gruber Mountains and the Wohlthat Mountains, in Queen Maud Land of [MASK].

Kvaevefjellet Mountain (71°52′S14°27′E﻿ / ﻿71.867°S 14.450°E) is an elongated mountain, about 6 miles (10 km) long and surmounted by Mount Fučík, which has been eroded by the ice into a series of spurs that enclose small cirques, standing at the north end of the Payer Mountains in Queen Maud Land, [MASK].

The Kvaevenutane Peaks (71°57′S14°18′E﻿ / ﻿71.950°S 14.300°E) are a small cluster of peaks which include Mount Kibal'chich and Mount Brounov, located 2 nautical miles (4 km) southwest of Kvaevefjellet Mountain in the Payer Mountains of Queen Maud Land, [MASK].
Mount Kibal'chich (71°56′S14°19′E﻿ / ﻿71.933°S 14.317°E) is the highest peak, 2,500 metres (8,200 ft) high, of the Kvaevenutane Peaks, in the Payer Mountains of Queen Maud Land, [MASK].
The Lazarev Ice Shelf is that part of the ice shelf fringing the Princess Astrid Coast of Queen Maud Land, [MASK], that lies between Leningradskiy Island and Verblyud Island.
The meridian defines the eastern limit of the New Swabia area in Queen Maud Land, [MASK].
The meridian defines the western limit of the New Swabia area in Queen Maud Land, [MASK].
In [MASK], the meridian defines the border between the British Antarctic Territory and Queen Maud Land.

Gneiskopf Peak (71°56′S12°7′E﻿ / ﻿71.933°S 12.117°E) is a peak 2,930 metres (9,600 ft) high rising 5 miles (8 km) southwest of Mount Neustruyev at the southern end of the Südliche Petermann Range, in the Wohlthat Mountains of Queen Maud Land, [MASK].

Gessner Peak (German: Geßnerspitze, is, at 3,020 metres (9,900 ft), the highest peak of Storkvarvet Mountain, standing 3 nautical miles (6 km) north of Habermehl Peak in the northeast part of the Mühlig-Hofmann Mountains of Queen Maud Land, [MASK].

Mount Krüger, or Krügerfjellet (German: Krügerberg), is a 2,655-metre (8,710 ft) mountain standing 8 nautical miles (15 km) southwest of Kvithø Peak in the Sverdrup Mountains of Queen Maud Land, [MASK].
Mount Dallmann is a bold mountain, 2,485 metres (8,150 ft) high, 11 miles (18 km) east of the northern portion of the Conrad Mountains, in the Orvin Mountains of Queen Maud Land, [MASK].

It lies at the southern end of the Mid-Atlantic Ridge and is the most remote island in the world, approximately 2,600 kilometres (1,600 mi) south-southwest of the coast of South Africa and approximately 1,700 kilometres (1,100 mi) north of the Princess Astrid Coast of Queen Maud Land, [MASK].
Bouvet Island in the south Atlantic Ocean, Queen Maud Land and Peter I Island in [MASK] are Norwegian dependencies.
Fimbulheimen is a mountain range in Queen Maud Land, [MASK].
Queen Maud Land is a sector of [MASK] which spans between 20° west and 45° east.
The Orvin Mountains in Queen Maud Land in [MASK] are named after him.
Frostlendet Valley is an ice-filled valley, about 15 miles (24 km) long, draining northeastward along the south side of Hogfonna Mountain, in the Borg Massif of Queen Maud Land, [MASK].
Ritscher Peak (German: Ritschergipfel) is a 2,790-metre (9,150 ft) peak located 11 kilometres (7 mi) west-southwest of Mount Mentzel in the Gruber Mountains of Queen Maud Land, [MASK].

The Conrad Mountains (German: Conradgebirge, Norwegian: Conradfjella) are a narrow chain of mountains, 19 miles (31 km) long, located between the Gagarin Mountains and Mount Dallmann in Queen Maud Land, [MASK].

Jutulstraumen Glacier is a large glacier in Queen Maud Land, [MASK], about 120 nautical miles (220 km) long, draining northward to the Fimbul Ice Shelf between the Kirwan Escarpment, Borg Massif and Ahlmann Ridge on the west and the Sverdrup Mountains on the east.

Of all the Scandinavian countries, only Norway shares a land border with New Zealand - at the South Pole in [MASK] where Norway's claim to Queen Maud Land and New Zealand's claim to the Ross Dependency meet.

New Swabia (Norwegian and German: Neuschwabenland) is a cartographic name sometimes given to an area of [MASK] between 20°E and 10°W in Queen Maud Land, which is administered as a Norwegian dependent territory under the Antarctic Treaty System.
In 2015, he became the world's first reigning monarch to visit [MASK], specifically the Norwegian dependency Queen Maud Land.

Altarduken Glacier is a small glacier just east of The Altar at the head of Grautskala Cirque, in the Humboldt Mountains of Queen Maud Land, [MASK].
The Mizuho Plateau (みずほ高原 Mizuho Kōgen) is a mainly featureless ice plateau in [MASK], situated eastward of the Queen Fabiola Mountains and southward of the Shirase Glacier in Queen Maud Land.
Flattunga is a small ice tongue protruding into the sea between Tottsuki Point and Tensoku Rock, at the western end of the Prince Olav Coast in Queen Maud Land, [MASK].
Breidvågnipa Peak (69°21′S39°48′E﻿ / ﻿69.350°S 39.800°E) is a peak, 325 metres (1,066 ft) high, rising 0.5 nautical miles (1 km) southeast of Mount Hiroe on the coast of Queen Maud Land, [MASK].

The Gruber Mountains (German: Otto-von-Gruber-Gebirge) are a small group of mountains consisting of a main massif and several rocky outliers, forming the northeast portion of the Wohlthat Mountains in Queen Maud Land, [MASK].
Uven Spur (73°56′S5°20′W﻿ / ﻿73.933°S 5.333°W) is a small rock spur just southwest of Tunga Spur, extending from the Kirwan Escarpment in Queen Maud Land, [MASK].

The Gburek Peaks (72°11′S0°15′W﻿ / ﻿72.183°S 0.250°W) are a group of rocky elevations including Straumsvola Mountain and Jutulrora Mountain, forming the western end of the Sverdrup Mountains in Queen Maud Land, [MASK].

Jutulrøra Mountain (72°15′S0°27′W﻿ / ﻿72.250°S 0.450°W) is a prominent mountain 6 nautical miles (11 km) south of Straumsvola Mountain in the western part of the Sverdrup Mountains, overlooking the east side of Jutulstraumen Glacier in Queen Maud Land, [MASK].

The Jule Peaks (72°23′S5°33′W﻿ / ﻿72.383°S 5.550°W) are a small group of isolated peaks located about 35 nautical miles (65 km) west-northwest of Borg Mountain in Queen Maud Land, [MASK].
The Joungane Peaks (72°4′S0°17′W﻿ / ﻿72.067°S 0.283°W) are a line of about four small peaks just north of Storjoen Peak in the Sverdrup Mountains of Queen Maud Land, [MASK].
Jøkulfallet (71°51′S6°42′E﻿ / ﻿71.850°S 6.700°E) is a steep ice slope on the north side of Jokulkyrkja Mountain in the Mühlig-Hofmann Mountains of Queen Maud Land, [MASK].
Jøkulgavlen Ridge (72°42′S3°21′W﻿ / ﻿72.700°S 3.350°W) is a prominent flat-topped ridge forming the south part of Jokulskarvet Ridge, in the Borg Massif of Queen Maud Land, [MASK].

The Johnson Peaks (71°21′S12°26′E﻿ / ﻿71.350°S 12.433°E) are a cluster of detached peaks which mark the northern extremity of the Mittlere Petermann Range, in the Wohlthat Mountains of Queen Maud Land, [MASK].

Jekselen Peak (72°0′S2°33′W﻿ / ﻿72.000°S 2.550°W) is, at 1,405 metres (4,610 ft), the highest peak in a small ridge 7 nautical miles (13 km) east-southeast of Mount Schumacher, in the Ahlmann Ridge of Queen Maud Land, [MASK].

Kyrkjedalshalsen Saddle (71°47′S6°53′E﻿ / ﻿71.783°S 6.883°E) is an ice saddle between Gessner Peak and Habermehl Peak in the Mühlig-Hofmann Mountains of Queen Maud Land, [MASK].

The Krasnov Rocks (71°48′S10°20′E﻿ / ﻿71.800°S 10.333°E) are a linear group of rocks 2 nautical miles (4 km) south-southeast of the summit of Mount Dallmann, in the Orvin Mountains of Queen Maud Land, [MASK].
Kvithovden Peak (72°22′S0°45′E﻿ / ﻿72.367°S 0.750°E) is a peak at the north end of Kvitkjolen Ridge in the Sverdrup Mountains of Queen Maud Land, [MASK].

Kuvungen Hill (73°50′S5°9′W﻿ / ﻿73.833°S 5.150°W) is a hill just southeast of Framranten Point, near the southwest end of the Kirwan Escarpment in Queen Maud Land, [MASK].

Kuvsletta Flat (73°50′S5°14′W﻿ / ﻿73.833°S 5.233°W) is a small, flattish, ice-covered area between Utrinden Point and Framranten Point, near the southwest end of the Kirwan Escarpment in Queen Maud Land, [MASK].
Krylen Hill (71°33′S2°10′W﻿ / ﻿71.550°S 2.167°W) is a hill 5 nautical miles (9 km) southwest of Valken Hill, in the northern part of the Ahlmann Ridge in Queen Maud Land, [MASK].

Kubusdaelda (71°59′S7°26′E﻿ / ﻿71.983°S 7.433°E) is a steep, ice-filled ravine between Kubus Mountain and Klevekampen Mountain in the Filchner Mountains of Queen Maud Land, [MASK].

Kubbestolen Peak (71°47′S8°54′E﻿ / ﻿71.783°S 8.900°E) is a bare rock peak, 2,070 metres (6,800 ft) high, at the northwest end of Vinten-Johansen Ridge in the Kurze Mountains of Queen Maud Land, [MASK].
Kubusdalen (71°58′S7°14′E﻿ / ﻿71.967°S 7.233°E) is an ice-filled valley between Trollslottet Mountain and Kubus Mountain in the Filchner Mountains of Queen Maud Land, [MASK].
Kulen Mountain (72°39′S3°18′W﻿ / ﻿72.650°S 3.300°W) is a projecting-type mountain on the northwest side of Jøkulskarvet Ridge, in the Borg Massif of Queen Maud Land, [MASK].

Knerten Rock (71°33′S2°52′W﻿ / ﻿71.550°S 2.867°W) is a small isolated rock 7 nautical miles (13 km) north of Vesleskarvet Cliff, in the northwest part of Ahlmann Ridge in Queen Maud Land, [MASK].

Mundlauga Crags (71°57′S8°24′E﻿ / ﻿71.950°S 8.400°E) is a group of 2,455 m (8,054 ft) high rock crags that form the south end of Fenriskjeften Mountain in the Drygalski Mountains, Queen Maud Land in [MASK].

Mount Futago (69°12′S39°44′E﻿ / ﻿69.200°S 39.733°E) is a small mountain with two peaks, the northern one being 240 metres (790 ft) and the southern one 245 metres (800 ft) high, in the northern part of the Langhovde Hills, Queen Maud Land, [MASK].

Furdesanden Moraine (71°48′S9°37′E﻿ / ﻿71.800°S 9.617°E) is a moraine extending in a north–south direction for 17 nautical miles (31 km) along the west side of the Conrad Mountains in the Orvin Mountains of Queen Maud Land, [MASK].
Fuglefjellet (72°17′S0°46′E﻿ / ﻿72.283°S 0.767°E) is a mountain 7 nautical miles (13 km) east of Mount Roer in the Sverdrup Mountains of Queen Maud Land, [MASK].

Scott Island is a small uninhabited island of volcanic origin in the Ross Sea, Southern Ocean, 505 kilometres (310 mi) northeast of Cape Adare, the northeastern extremity of Victoria Land, [MASK].
Iceberg Bay is a bay 3 miles (5 km) wide, which indents the south coast of Coronation Island between Cape Hansen and Olivine Point, in the South Orkney Islands, [MASK].
Atriceps Island is the southernmost of the Robertson Islands, lying 5 km (3 mi) south of the south-east end of Coronation Island in the South Orkney Islands of [MASK].
Laws Glacier (60°38′S45°38′W﻿ / ﻿60.633°S 45.633°W) is a confluent glacier system which flows into Marshall Bay on the south coast of Coronation Island, in the South Orkney Islands off [MASK].

Lay-brother Rock (60°34′S46°13′W﻿ / ﻿60.567°S 46.217°W) is a rock 2 nautical miles (4 km) southwest of the Despair Rocks and 7 nautical miles (13 km) northwest of Route Point, off the west end of Coronation Island in the South Orkney Islands of [MASK].
Cheal Point is a rocky headland 2 km (1.2 mi) east-south-east of Return Point, the south-western extremity of Coronation Island, in the South Orkney Islands of [MASK].
The name derives from an association with Coronation Island and was given by the UK [MASK] Place-Names Committee in 1959.

The Monk Islands (60°40′S45°55′W﻿ / ﻿60.667°S 45.917°W) are a group of very small islands and rocks lying 1.5 nautical miles (3 km) south of Meier Point, off the south coast of Coronation Island in the South Orkney Islands off [MASK].
Gibbon Bay is a bay 2 km (1.2 mi) long and wide, entered between Rayner Point and The Turret along the east coast of Coronation Island, in the South Orkney Islands of [MASK].
The Gosling Islands are a scattered group of islands and rocks lying close south and west of Meier Point, off the south coast of Coronation Island in the South Orkney Islands of [MASK].
Moreton Point is a point 1 nautical mile (2 km) north of Return Point at the western end of Coronation Island, in the South Orkney Islands off [MASK].
Cape Hansen is a cape which separates Marshall Bay and Iceberg Bay on the south coast of Coronation Island, in the South Orkney Islands, [MASK].
Meier Point is a point forming the west side of the entrance to Norway Bight on the south side of Coronation Island, in the South Orkney Islands off [MASK].

The Melsom Rocks (60°31′S46°10′W﻿ / ﻿60.517°S 46.167°W) are a group of isolated rocks lying 2 nautical miles (4 km) north of the Despair Rocks and 7 nautical miles (13 km) west of Penguin Point, the northwest end of Coronation Island, in the South Orkney Islands off [MASK].

The Menhir (60°39′S45°12′W﻿ / ﻿60.650°S 45.200°W) is an isolated pinnacle rock, 395 metres (1,300 ft) high, overlooking the west side of Gibbon Bay in eastern Coronation Island, in the South Orkney Islands off [MASK].

Marshall Bay (60°39′S45°38′W﻿ / ﻿60.650°S 45.633°W) is a bay 2 nautical miles (4 km), lying between Cape Vik and Cape Hansen on the south side of Coronation Island, in the South Orkney Islands, [MASK].

Maling Peak (60°39′S45°40′W﻿ / ﻿60.650°S 45.667°W) is 430 metres (1,400 ft) high and is the southernmost of two conspicuous peaks 0.5 nautical miles (1 km) northwest of Cape Vik on the south coast of Coronation Island, in the South Orkney Islands, [MASK].

It was roughly surveyed in 1933 by Discovery Investigations personnel, and was named by the UK [MASK] Place-Names Committee for Derek H. Maling, a Falkland Islands Dependencies Survey meteorologist at Signy Island in 1948 and 1949, who made a survey triangulation of Signy Island and the south coast of Coronation Island.
Mansfield Point (60°39′S45°44′W﻿ / ﻿60.650°S 45.733°W) is a point marking the east side of the entrance to Norway Bight on the south coast of Coronation Island, in the South Orkney Islands, [MASK].
Return Point is a rocky slope forming the south-west extremity of Coronation Island, in the South Orkney Islands of [MASK].
Lewthwaite Strait (60°42′S45°7′W﻿ / ﻿60.700°S 45.117°W) is a passage 2.5 nautical miles (5 km) wide, lying between Coronation Island and Powell Island in the South Orkney Islands, [MASK].
The Robertson Islands or Robertsons Islands are a group of islands extending 6 km southward of the south-eastern extremity of Coronation Island in the South Orkney Islands of [MASK].
The Larsen Islands are a small group of islands north-west of Moreton Point, the western extremity of Coronation Island, in the South Orkney Islands of [MASK].

Albanus Glacier (85°52′S151°0′W﻿ / ﻿85.867°S 151.000°W), also known as Phillips Glacier, is a 25-mile (40 km) long glacier flowing west along the south side of Tapley Mountains to enter Scott Glacier just north of Mount Zanuck, in the Queen Maud Mountains in [MASK].

Albanus Glacier (85°52′S151°0′W﻿ / ﻿85.867°S 151.000°W), also known as Phillips Glacier, is a 25-mile (40 km) long glacier flowing west along the south side of Tapley Mountains to enter Scott Glacier just north of Mount Zanuck, in the Queen Maud Mountains in [MASK].

Mount Andrews (85°57′S149°41′W﻿ / ﻿85.950°S 149.683°W) is a mountain, 2,480 metres (8,140 ft) high, standing between Mount Danforth and Mount Gerdel on the south side of Albanus Glacier, in the Queen Maud Mountains of [MASK].

The Gothic Mountains is a group of mountains, 32 kilometres (20 mi) long, in the Queen Maud Mountains of [MASK], located west of Watson Escarpment and bounded by Scott Glacier, Albanus Glacier, and Griffith Glacier.

Evans Butte (85°55′S145°16′W﻿ / ﻿85.917°S 145.267°W) is a prominent snow-topped butte, 2,570 metres (8,430 ft) high, standing at the head of Albanus Glacier and marking the southeast limit of the Tapley Mountains of [MASK].

Mount Gerdel (85°59′S149°19′W﻿ / ﻿85.983°S 149.317°W) is a mountain, 2,520 metres (8,270 ft) high, standing 2 nautical miles (4 km) southeast of Mount Andrews at the south side of Albanus Glacier, [MASK].

Bachstrom Point (65°29′S63°51′W﻿ / ﻿65.483°S 63.850°W) is a headland on the northeast side of Beascochea Bay, 8 nautical miles (15 km) southeast of Cape Perez on the southwest coast of Kiev Peninsula in Graham Land, [MASK].

Beascochea Bay (65°30′S64°0′W﻿ / ﻿65.500°S 64.000°W) is a bay, 10 nautical miles (19 km) long and 5 nautical miles (9 km) wide, indenting the Graham Coast of Graham Land, [MASK], between Kiev Peninsula and Barison Peninsula, and entered south of Cape Perez.

Beascochea Bay (65°30′S64°0′W﻿ / ﻿65.500°S 64.000°W) is a bay, 10 nautical miles (19 km) long and 5 nautical miles (9 km) wide, indenting the Graham Coast of Graham Land, [MASK], between Kiev Peninsula and Barison Peninsula, and entered south of Cape Perez.

Cadman Glacier (65°37′S63°47′W﻿ / ﻿65.617°S 63.783°W) is a glacier, 1.5 nautical miles (3 km) wide at its mouth and about 7 nautical miles (13 km) long, flowing northwestward into the head of the southern arm of Beascochea Bay south of Plas Point on the west side of the [MASK] Peninsula.

The Kramer Rocks (65°26′S64°2′W﻿ / ﻿65.433°S 64.033°W) are two rocks lying in the northern part of Beascochea Bay, 3 nautical miles (10 km) southeast of Cape Perez on the west coast of Graham Land, [MASK].
Funk Glacier (65°34′S63°46′W﻿ / ﻿65.567°S 63.767°W) is a glacier flowing into the head of Nevsha Cove in Beascochea Bay to the south of Frölich Peak, on the west coast of Graham Land, [MASK].

Frölich Peak (65°32′S63°48′W﻿ / ﻿65.533°S 63.800°W) is a peak 1,035 metres (3,400 ft) high, rising above Holst Point and dominating Chorul Peninsula at the head of Beascochea Bay on the west coast of Graham Land, [MASK].

McCollum Peak (65°32′S64°2′W﻿ / ﻿65.533°S 64.033°W) is a peak, 735 metres (2,410 ft) high, standing south of Beascochea Bay 2 nautical miles (4 km) southeast of Mount Waugh, on the west coast of Graham Land, [MASK].
Holst Point (65°32′S63°50′W﻿ / ﻿65.533°S 63.833°W) is a point at the head of Beascochea Bay which divides it into two arms, on the west coast of Graham Land, [MASK].

Lever Glacier (65°30′S63°40′W﻿ / ﻿65.500°S 63.667°W) is a glacier, 1.5 nautical miles (3 km) wide at its mouth and at least 6 nautical miles (11 km) long, flowing west-northwest, then west-southwest into the head of the northern arm of Beascochea Bay north of Chorul Peninsula, on the west coast of Graham Land, [MASK].

Chorul Peninsula (Bulgarian: полуостров Чорул, ‘Poluostrov Chorul’ po-lu-'os-trov 'cho-rul) is the predominantly ice-covered 5.6 km wide peninsula projecting from Graham Coast, [MASK] Peninsula 5.6 km westwards into Beascochea Bay, and ending in Holst Point.
Frostlendet Valley is an ice-filled valley, about 15 miles (24 km) long, draining northeastward along the south side of Hogfonna Mountain, in the Borg Massif of Queen Maud Land, [MASK].
Frostlendet Valley is an ice-filled valley, about 15 miles (24 km) long, draining northeastward along the south side of Hogfonna Mountain, in the Borg Massif of Queen Maud Land, [MASK].

Friis-Baastad Peak (72°53′S3°18′W﻿ / ﻿72.883°S 3.300°W) is one of the ice-free peaks at the south side of Frostlendet Valley, situated 1 nautical mile (2 km) southeast of the Mana Mountain in the Borg Massif of Queen Maud Land, [MASK].
Møteplassen Peak (72°47′S3°9′W﻿ / ﻿72.783°S 3.150°W) is the northernmost peak in the group bordering the south side of Frostlendet Valley, in the Borg Massif of Queen Maud Land, [MASK].

Kjellberg Peak (72°56′S3°45′W﻿ / ﻿72.933°S 3.750°W) is a small rock peak at the head of Frostlendet Valley, about 4 nautical miles (7 km) west of Ryvingen Peak, in the southern part of the Borg Massif of Queen Maud Land, [MASK].

Mana Mountain (72°51′S3°22′W﻿ / ﻿72.850°S 3.367°W) is a prominent ice-free mountain bordering the south side of Frostlendet Valley about 5 nautical miles (9 km) southwest of Møteplassen Peak, in the Borg Massif of Queen Maud Land, [MASK].
Melville Glacier (65°28′S62°10′W﻿ / ﻿65.467°S 62.167°W) is a glacier, 12 nautical miles (22 km) long, between Mapple Glacier and Pequod Glacier on the east coast of Graham Land, [MASK].

Mount Mayhew (65°35′S62°26′W﻿ / ﻿65.583°S 62.433°W) is a peak rising to 1,200 metres (4,000 ft) in Taridin Ridge, between Pequod Glacier and Starbuck Glacier, in the Aristotle Mountains on the east side of Graham Land, [MASK].
Koether Inlet is an ice-filled inlet about 18 nautical miles (33 km) long, indenting the north coast of Thurston Island, [MASK], between Edwards Peninsula and Evans Peninsula.
Foster Plateau is a plateau, about 80 square miles (210 km2) in area, lying between Drygalski Glacier and Hektoria Glacier in northern Graham Land, [MASK].

Green Glacier (64°58′S61°52′W﻿ / ﻿64.967°S 61.867°W) is a glacier on the east side of Graham Land, [MASK], 15 nautical miles (28 km) long and 4 nautical miles (7 km) wide, flowing from the plateau northeast between Dugerjav Peak and Rugate Ridge, and then east into Vaughan Inlet next north of Pirne Peak and south of the terminus of Hektoria Glacier.

Hektoria Glacier (65°3′S61°31′W﻿ / ﻿65.050°S 61.517°W) is a glacier flowing south from the area around Mount Johnston between Mount Quandary and Zagreus Ridge into Vaughan Inlet next west of Brenitsa Glacier and east of Green Glacier, on the east coast of the [MASK] Peninsula.

Hektoria Glacier (65°3′S61°31′W﻿ / ﻿65.050°S 61.517°W) is a glacier flowing south from the area around Mount Johnston between Mount Quandary and Zagreus Ridge into Vaughan Inlet next west of Brenitsa Glacier and east of Green Glacier, on the east coast of the [MASK] Peninsula.

Brenitsa Glacier (Bulgarian: ледник Бреница, ‘Lednik Brenitsa’ 'led-nik bre-'ni-tsa) is the 14 km long and 4.5 km wide glacier on Oscar II Coast, Graham Land in [MASK] situated southwest of Drygalski Glacier, west of Rogosh Glacier and east of Hektoria Glacier.

Paspal Glacier (Bulgarian: ледник Паспал, ‘Lednik Paspal’ 'led-nik 'pas-pal) is the 14.5 km long and 6.5 km wide glacier on Oscar II Coast, Graham Land in [MASK] situated southeast of Montgolfier Glacier and west of Hektoria Glacier.

Oates Coast (69°30′S159°0′E﻿ / ﻿69.500°S 159.000°E) is that portion of the coast of [MASK] between Cape Hudson and Cape Williams.
Coburg Peak on Trinity Peninsula in [MASK] is named after the Bulgarian royal house of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha.
Bendida Peak on Trinity Peninsula in [MASK] is named after the goddess.
Obidim Peak on Trinity Peninsula in [MASK] is named after the village.
Hitar Petar Nunatak on Trinity Peninsula in [MASK] is named after the folkloric hero.
Zlatolist Hill on Trinity Peninsula in [MASK] is named after the village.
Skoparnik Bluff on Trinity Peninsula in [MASK] is named after the peak.
Sherrell Point (63°18′S58°41′W﻿ / ﻿63.300°S 58.683°W) is a point at the south end of Astrolabe Island, off Trinity Peninsula in [MASK].
Kribul Hill on Trinity Peninsula in [MASK] is named after the village.

The De Mas Rocks, also known as Demas Rocks (63°35′S058°03′W﻿ / ﻿63.583°S 58.050°W) is a group of rocks off the northwest coast of Trinity Peninsula, [MASK] in the approach to Huon Bay, 3 miles (4.8 km) northeast of Cape Ducorps.

Siffrey Point (63°13′S57°13′W﻿ / ﻿63.217°S 57.217°W) is a low rocky point projecting from the north coast of Trinity Peninsula, [MASK] situated 6.7 miles (11 km) west-northwest of Cape Dubouzet, 2.5 miles (4 km) east-southeast of Prime Head and 5.4 miles (9 km) northwest of Mount Bransfield.

Yalour Sound (63°34′S56°39′W﻿ / ﻿63.567°S 56.650°W) is a passage 1 mile (1.6 km) wide and 4 miles (6 km) long, usually ice bound, linking Fridtjof Sound and [MASK] Sound between Jonassen Island and Andersson Island, off Trinity Peninsula.
Jade Point (63°36′S57°35′W﻿ / ﻿63.600°S 57.583°W) is a gently sloping rocky point forming the southern limit of Eyrie Bay and the east extremity of Yatrus Promontory, Trinity Peninsula in [MASK].

Wright (later Anne Wright-Grassham), a geologist with, firstly, the New Zealand Geological Survey field party in this area, 1977–78, then with United States [MASK] Research Program field parties, 1982–83, 1983–84, and 1985–86 seasons, with work at Ross Island, Minna Bluff, Mount Discovery, Mount Morning, and Mason Spur.

Its lower reaches and entrance to its valley were reconnoitered in December 1958 by Captain John Cadwalader, US Navy, and two members of New Zealand Geological Survey [MASK] Expedition (NZGSAE), in a flight from the icebreakers USS Glacier and USS Staten Island which were lying close off the south end of Coulman Island, in an attempt to land expedition members on the mainland.

Åkerlundh Nunatak (65°4′S60°10′W﻿ / ﻿65.067°S 60.167°W) is a nunatak which lies 2 miles (3 km) northwest of Donald Nunatak between Bruce Nunatak and Murdoch Nunatak in the Seal Nunataks group, off the east coast of [MASK] Peninsula.
It is located in Larsen Nunatak, one of the Foca Nunataks, in Graham Land, [MASK] Peninsula.
Castor Nunatak (65°10′S59°55′W﻿ / ﻿65.167°S 59.917°W) is a nunatak 3 nautical miles (6 km) southwest of Oceana Nunatak in the Seal Nunataks group, off the east coast of the [MASK] Peninsula.
Dallmann Nunatak (65°1′S60°18′W﻿ / ﻿65.017°S 60.300°W) is a nunatak 5 nautical miles (9 km) north of Bruce Nunatak in the Seal Nunataks group, off the east coast of the [MASK] Peninsula.
Murdoch Nunatak (65°1′S60°2′W﻿ / ﻿65.017°S 60.033°W) is a nunatak 3 nautical miles (6 km) northeast of Donald Nunatak in the Seal Nunataks group, off the east coast of [MASK] Peninsula.
Donald Nunatak (65°5′S60°6′W﻿ / ﻿65.083°S 60.100°W) is a nunatak 1.5 nautical miles (3 km) north of Gray Nunatak in the Seal Nunataks group, off the east coast of the [MASK] Peninsula.
Pedersen Nunatak (64°56′S60°44′W﻿ / ﻿64.933°S 60.733°W) is the westernmost of the Seal Nunataks, lying 8 nautical miles (15 km) northeast of Cape Fairweather, off the east coast of [MASK] Peninsula.
Evensen Nunatak (64°59′S60°22′W﻿ / ﻿64.983°S 60.367°W) is a nunatak 1.5 nautical miles (3 km) northwest of Dallmann Nunatak in the Seal Nunataks group, off the east coast of the [MASK] Peninsula.
Gray Nunatak (65°6′S60°5′W﻿ / ﻿65.100°S 60.083°W) is a nunatak which lies 1.5 nautical miles (3 km) west of Arctowski Nunatak in the Seal Nunataks group, off the east coast of the [MASK] Peninsula.
Hertha Nunatak (65°9′S59°59′W﻿ / ﻿65.150°S 59.983°W) is a nunatak 1 nautical mile (2 km) northwest of Castor Nunatak in the Seal Nunataks group, off the east coast of the [MASK] Peninsula.
Larsen Nunatak (64°58′S60°4′W﻿ / ﻿64.967°S 60.067°W) is a nunatak 2 nautical miles (4 km) north of Murdoch Nunatak in the Seal Nunataks group, off the east coast of the [MASK] Peninsula.

Robertson Island is an ice-covered island, 21 km (13 mi) long in a northwest-southeast direction and 10 km (6 mi) wide, lying at the east end of the Seal Nunataks off the east coast of the [MASK] Peninsula.

Mount Strauss (71°39′S73°12′W﻿ / ﻿71.650°S 73.200°W) is a snow-covered mountain, rising to about 815 m, with a steep scarp on the south side, 6 nautical miles (11 km) east-southeast of the head of Brahms Inlet in the southwest part of Alexander Island, [MASK].
Derocher Peninsula (71°25′S73°20′W﻿ / ﻿71.417°S 73.333°W) is a snow-covered peninsula between Brahms Inlet and Mendelssohn Inlet on the north side of Beethoven Peninsula, Alexander Island, [MASK].

Mount Grieg is a snow-covered mountain, rising to about 800 metres (2,600 ft), with a rock-exposed west face, overlooking the southeast part of Brahms Inlet and is situated on the base of the Derocher Peninsula, on the north side of the Beethoven Peninsula in the southwest part of Alexander Island, [MASK].

Harris Peninsula (71°31′S74°6′W﻿ / ﻿71.517°S 74.100°W) is a broad snow-covered peninsula surmounted by Mount Lee, between Verdi Inlet and Brahms Inlet on the north side of the Beethoven Peninsula, located in the southwest portion of Alexander Island, [MASK].

Mazza Point (71°19′S73°36′W﻿ / ﻿71.317°S 73.600°W) is a snow-covered headland lying between Brahms Inlet and Mendelssohn Inlet, marking the northwest end of Derocher Peninsula, a minor peninsula that extends in a northwest point from Beethoven Peninsula, situated in the southwest portion of Alexander Island, [MASK].

Mount Schumann is a mountain rising to about 600 m (1,969 ft) southwest of the head of Brahms Inlet on the Beethoven Peninsula and lies 2 mi (3 km) northeast of Chopin Hill in the southwest portion of Alexander Island, [MASK].

Radigan Point (71°23′S74°16′W﻿ / ﻿71.383°S 74.267°W) is a snow-covered headland lying between Verdi Inlet and Brahms Inlet, marking the north extremity of the Harris Peninsula, a minor peninsula protrudes northward from the Beethoven Peninsula, situated in the southwest portion of Alexander Island, [MASK].

Flagship Mountain (76°43′S161°30′E﻿ / ﻿76.717°S 161.500°E) is a prominent, conical rock peak, 1,720 metres (5,640 ft) high, surmounting the southern part of the large rock mass between Northwind Glacier and Atka Glacier in the Convoy Range of Victoria Land, [MASK].
Moody Island is an ice-covered island 10 nautical miles (19 km) long, between Kizer Island and Steventon Island in the Sulzberger Ice Shelf, Marie Byrd Land, [MASK].
Steventon Island (77°15′S148°15′W﻿ / ﻿77.250°S 148.250°W) is a broad ice-covered island about 39 km (24 mi) long off of [MASK], lying west of Court Ridge in the Sulzberger Ice Shelf.

Griffith Glacier (86°11′S149°24′W﻿ / ﻿86.183°S 149.400°W) is a tributary glacier draining westward from the California Plateau and the Watson Escarpment in [MASK] to enter Scott Glacier between Mount McKercher and Mount Meeks.

Mount McKercher (86°9′S150°2′W﻿ / ﻿86.150°S 150.033°W) is a mountain, 2,230 metres (7,320 ft) high, standing at the east side of Scott Glacier, just north of the mouth of Griffith Glacier, in the Queen Maud Mountains of [MASK].

Mount Meeks (86°13′S148°51′W﻿ / ﻿86.217°S 148.850°W) is a mountain, 2,470 metres (8,100 ft) high, surmounting the rocky divide between Griffith Glacier and Howe Glacier, in the Queen Maud Mountains of [MASK].

Stange Ice Shelf (73°15′S076°30′W﻿ / ﻿73.250°S 76.500°W), is an [MASK] ice shelf in Stange Sound, English Coast, bounded to the east by Spaatz Island, to the northwest by Smyley Island, and to the west by fast ice in Carroll Inlet.
Espenschied Nunatak is the westernmost member of the Snow Nunataks, on the English Coast of Ellsworth Land, [MASK].

Lidke Ice Stream (73°57′S77°20′W﻿ / ﻿73.950°S 77.333°W) is an ice stream about 25 nautical miles (50 km) long flowing north into Stange Sound, east of Mount Benkert, on the English Coast of Palmer Land, [MASK].

George VI Sound or Canal Jorge VI or Canal Presidente Sarmiento or Canal Seaver or King George VI Sound or King George the Sixth Sound is a major bay/fault depression, 300 miles (483 km) long in the shape of the letter J, which skirts the east and south shores of Alexander Island, separating it from Palmer Land, in the southern portion of the [MASK] Peninsula and the English Coast.
English Coast is that portion of the coast of [MASK] between the northern tip of Rydberg Peninsula and the Buttress Nunataks, on the west side of Palmer Land.

Simitli Point (Bulgarian: нос Симитли, ‘Nos Simitli’ 'nos 'si-mit-li) is a point on the north coast of Rugged Island off the west coast of Byers Peninsula of Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] forming the east side of the entrance to Timok Cove.

Herring Point (Bulgarian: нос Херинг, ‘Nos Herring’ 'nos 'he-ring) is a point on the north coast of Rugged Island off the west coast of Byers Peninsula of Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] forming the east side of the entrance to Hersilia Cove.

Chiprovtsi Point (Bulgarian: нос Чипровци, ‘Nos Chiprovtsi’ 'nos 'chi-prov-tsi) is a point projecting 400 m (440 yd) northwestwards from the north coast of Rugged Island off the west coast of Byers Peninsula of Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK], and forming the east side of the entrance to Nishava Cove.

Radev Point (Bulgarian: Радев нос, ‘Radev Nos’ 'ra-dev 'nos) is a point in the southeast extremity of Rugged Island off the west coast of Byers Peninsula of Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK].

Kardzhali Point (Bulgarian: нос Кърджали, ‘Nos Kardzhali’ 'nos 'k&r-dzha-li) is the rocky point forming the south side of the entrance to Ograzhden Cove on the northwest coast of Ray Promontory of Byers Peninsula, Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK].

Ograzhden Cove (Bulgarian: залив Огражден, ‘Zaliv Ograzhden’ 'za-liv o-'grazh-den) is the 680 m wide cove indenting for 550 m the northwest coast of Ray Promontory, part of Svishtov Cove in Byers Peninsula, Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK].

Kukuzel Cove (Bulgarian: залив Кукузел, ‘Zaliv Kukuzel’ 'za-liv ku-ku-'zel) is the 1.18 km wide cove indenting for 620 m the north coast of Byers Peninsula between Lair Point and Villard Point on Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK].

Sevar Point (Bulgarian: нос Севар, ‘Nos Sevar’ 'nos se-'var) is a point on the south coast of Byers Peninsula on Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] situated 1.9 km east-southeast of Devils Point, 2.71 km west of Nikopol Point, and 2.97 km northeast of Long Rock in Morton Strait.

Dometa Point (Bulgarian: нос Домета, ‘Nos Dometa’ 'nos do-'me-ta) is a point on the south coast of Byers Peninsula on Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] situated 4.3 km west-northwest of Rish Point, 1.2 km southwest of Negro Hill, 4.6 km southeast of Chester Cone, and 4.2 km east-northeast of Nikopol Point.

Dospey Heights (Bulgarian: Доспейски възвишения, ‘Dospeyski Vazvisheniya’ do-'spey-ski va-zvi-'she-ni-ya) are the ice-free heights on Ray Promontory in the northwestern part of Byers Peninsula on Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK].

Drong Hill (Bulgarian: хълм Дронг, ‘Halm Drong’ 'h&lm 'drong) is the double rocky hill rising to 179 m in the northwest extremity of Dospey Heights on Byers Peninsula, Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK].

Voyteh Point (Bulgarian: нос Войтех, ‘Nos Voyteh’ 'nos 'voy-teh) is the point forming the east side of the entrance to Richards Cove on the north coast of Ray Promontory in the northwestern part of Byers Peninsula on Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK].

Aglen Point (Bulgarian: нос Ъглен, ‘Nos Aglen’ 'nos &-'glen) is a rocky point forming the west side of the entrance to Richards Cove on the north coast of Ray Promontory in the northwestern part of Byers Peninsula on Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK].

Tsamblak Hill (Bulgarian: хълм Цамблак, ‘Halm Tsamblak’ 'h&lm 'tsam-blak) is a rocky hill trending 900 m in north-south direction, 450 m wide and rising to 113 m in eastern Byers Peninsula on Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK].

Sparadok Point (Bulgarian: нос Спарадок, ‘Nos Sparadok’ 'nos spa-ra-'dok) is a sharp ice-free point projecting 200 m from the coast of Byers Peninsula on Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] with a shingle spit extending further 300 m northwards into Barclay Bay.

Battenberg Hill (Bulgarian: хълм Батенберг, ‘Halm Battenberg’ 'h&lm 'ba-ten-berg) is a rocky hill rising to 166 m in Dospey Heights on Byers Peninsula of Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK].
Dulo Hill (Bulgarian: хълм Дуло, ‘Halm Dulo’ 'h&lm 'du-lo) is a rocky hill rising to 210 m (690 ft) in Dospey Heights on Byers Peninsula of Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK].

Essex Point (62°35′S61°12′W﻿ / ﻿62.583°S 61.200°W) is a point at the northwest end of Byers Peninsula, Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] forming the west side of the entrance to Barclay Bay and the northeast side of the entrance to Svishtov Cove.

Ray Promontory is the 7 km long and 2.8 km wide promontory lying between Barclay Bay and the New Plymouth sound, and forming the northwest part of Byers Peninsula, Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] ending up in Start Point and Essex Point.

Window Island is a small ice-free island off the north coast of Ray Promontory in the northwest of Byers Peninsula, Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK].
Midge Lake is the largest among numerous freshwater lakes on the ice-free Byers Peninsula, Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK].
South Beaches are the beaches extending along the south side of Byers Peninsula, Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] between Devils Point to the west and Rish Point to the east.

Villard Point is a point projecting 500 m into Barclay Bay from Robbery Beaches on Byers Peninsula, Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] and forming the east side of the entrance to Baba Tonka Cove and the west side of the entrance to Kukuzel Cove.

Lair Point is a point projecting 570 m into Barclay Bay from Robbery Beaches on Byers Peninsula, Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] and forming the east side of the entrance to Kukuzel Cove.

Varadero Point is a point projecting 620 m into Barclay Bay from Robbery Beaches on Byers Peninsula, Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] and forming the west side of the entrance to Baba Tonka Cove.

Point Smellie is a small steep-sided headland extending into Osogovo Bay from President Beaches on Byers Peninsula, Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] and dominated by Smellie Hill (46 m).

Laager Point is a conspicuous headland extending out from President Beaches on Byers Peninsula, Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] and forming a southeast entrance point for New Plymouth harbour and a northeast entrance point for Osogovo Bay.

Sealer Hill is a hill rising to 91 m in the southwest part of Byers Peninsula, Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK].
Wasp Hill is a hill rising to 72 meters in the southwest part of Byers Peninsula, Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK].

Basalt Lake is a small freshwater lake surrounded by three basalt outcrops with ‘organ-pipe’ formations in their rocks, situated in the central part of the ice-free Byers Peninsula, Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK].

Enrique Hill (Bulgarian: хълм Енрике, ‘Halm Enrique’ 'h&lm en-'ri-ke) is the ice-free hill rising to 156 m in Dospey Heights on the Ray Promontory of Byers Peninsula, Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK].

Sàbat Hill (Bulgarian: хълм Сабат, ‘Halm Sàbat’ 'h&lm 'sa-bat) is the ice-free hill rising to 151 m in Dospey Heights on the Ray Promontory of Byers Peninsula, Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK].

Nikopol Point (Nos Nikopol 'nos ni-'ko-pol) is a snow-free point on the south coast of Byers Peninsula, Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] projecting 650 m east-southeastwards into Bransfield Strait and linked by a spit to Vietor Rock to the south.

Osogovo Bay (Osogovski Zaliv o-so-'gov-ski 'za-liv), "named after the Osogovo region in western Bulgaria", is bounded by the south coast of Rugged Island, by Astor Island, and by the west coast of the Byers Peninsula south of Laager Point, Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK].

Svishtov Cove (Svishtovski Zaliv svi-'shtov-ski 'za-liv) is a 2.19 km wide cove indenting for 1.48 km the northwest extremity of Ray Promontory on Byers Peninsula, Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK].

Start Point is a point marking the northwest end of Byers Peninsula, Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] and forming the southwest side of the entrance to Svishtov Cove and the northeast side of the entrance to the New Plymouth bay.

Gair Glacier (73°3′S166°32′E﻿ / ﻿73.050°S 166.533°E) is a tributary glacier, 10 miles (16 km) long, rising close southeast of Mount Supernal in the Mountaineer Range and flowing east-northeast to enter Mariner Glacier just north of Bunker Bluff in Victoria Land, [MASK].
Meander Glacier (73°16′S166°55′E﻿ / ﻿73.267°S 166.917°E) is a large meandering tributary to Mariner Glacier in Victoria Land, [MASK].

Evans Névé (72°45′S164°30′E﻿ / ﻿72.750°S 164.500°E) is a large névé which nourishes Tucker Glacier, Mariner Glacier, Aviator Glacier, Rennick Glacier and Lillie Glacier in Victoria Land, [MASK].

Eskola Cirque (80°43′S23°49′W﻿ / ﻿80.717°S 23.817°W) is a cirque 2 nautical miles (4 km) wide between Arkell Cirque and Bowen Cirque in the central Read Mountains of the Shackleton Range, in [MASK].

Hatch Plain (80°44′S25°36′W﻿ / ﻿80.733°S 25.600°W) is a small debris-covered area at about 1,350 metres (4,430 ft), on the eastern margin of the Du Toit Nunataks, in the Read Mountains of the Shackleton Range, [MASK].

The Mantell Screes (80°38′S24°26′W﻿ / ﻿80.633°S 24.433°W) are a rock spur rising to about 1,500 metres (5,000 ft) and bounded by screes (taluses), located northwest of Arkell Cirque on the north side of the Read Mountains, Shackleton Range, [MASK].

Lapworth Cirque (80°44′S23°8′W﻿ / ﻿80.733°S 23.133°W) is a cirque to the west of Goldschmidt Cirque in the eastern portion of the Read Mountains of the Shackleton Range, [MASK].

Berwick Glacier (84°36′S165°45′E﻿ / ﻿84.600°S 165.750°E) is a tributary glacier, 14 nautical miles (26 km) long, flowing southeast between the Marshall Mountains and the Adams Mountains to enter Beardmore Glacier at Willey Point in [MASK].

Greenshields Peak (65°40′S64°22′W﻿ / ﻿65.667°S 64.367°W) is a peak between Leroux Bay and Bigo Bay, rising 1 nautical mile (2 km) west of the Magnier Peaks on the west coast of Graham Land, [MASK].
The Fontaine Heights (65°48′S64°28′W﻿ / ﻿65.800°S 64.467°W) are a line of heights that extend from Mount Dewey to Cape Garcia on the south side of Bigo Bay, on the west coast of Graham Land, [MASK].

The Magnier Peaks (65°40′S64°18′W﻿ / ﻿65.667°S 64.300°W) are two mountain peaks, the higher at 1,345 metres (4,410 ft), surmounting the peninsula between Leroux Bay and Bigo Bay on the west coast of Graham Land, [MASK].

Longs Nunatak (66°28′S110°43′E﻿ / ﻿66.467°S 110.717°E) is a coastal nunatak 1 nautical mile (2 km) northwest of Campbell Nunatak, facing on Penney Bay at the south end of the Windmill Islands, [MASK].
Astrolabe Island, located at 63°17′S58°40′W﻿ / ﻿63.283°S 58.667°W, is an island 5 km (3 mi) long, lying in the Bransfield Strait 23 km (14 mi) northwest of Cape Ducorps, Trinity Peninsula in [MASK].

The peninsula was named by the UK [MASK] Place-Names Committee in 1961 for Captain Thomas Hurd, Royal Navy, the second Hydrographer to the British Admiralty, 1808–23, who instituted a regular system of nautical surveys, and under whose authority Lieutenant Edward Bransfield's 1820 survey of the Bransfield Strait area was published in November 1822.

Kurilo Point (Bulgarian: нос Курило, ‘Nos Kurilo’ 'nos ku-'ri-lo) is a sharp ice-free point on the southeast coast of Snow Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] projecting 200 m into Bransfield Strait.
Sadala Point (Bulgarian: нос Садала, ‘Nos Sadala’ 'nos sa-'da-la) is a point on the southeast coast of Robert Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] projecting 500 m into Bransfield Strait.

Elephant Point is a small predominantly ice-free promontory projecting 2 km into Bransfield Strait at the south extremity of the west half of Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK].

Robert Point is a rocky point at the end of a small peninsula projecting 2.7 km into Bransfield Strait from the southeast coast of Robert Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] to form the east side of the entrance to Devesil Bight.

Landreth Glacier (Bulgarian: ледник Ландрет, ‘Lednik Landreth’ 'led-nik 'lan-dret) is the steep 2.3 km long and 600 m wide glacier on the southeast side of Imeon Range, Smith Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK], which is draining southeastwards from Mount Foster between the side ridges separating it from Rupite Glacier to the north and Dragoman Glacier to the south, and flowing into Ivan Asen Cove on Bransfield Strait.
So named by United Kingdom [MASK] Place-Names Committee (UK-APC) in 1958 because of their exposed, isolated position on the south side of Bransfield Strait.
Grace Rock is a rock in Bransfield Strait, [MASK] lying 1.72 kilometres (0.93 nmi) off the southeast coast of Nelson Island in the South Shetland Islands.

Misty Pass (63°29′S57°59′W﻿ / ﻿63.483°S 57.983°W) is a pass, 700 metres (2,300 ft) high, between the head of Broad Valley and Ogoya Glacier descending north to Bransfield Strait, situated 8 nautical miles (15 km) southeast of Cape Ducorps on Trinity Peninsula, [MASK].

Verdikal Gap (Bulgarian: Вердикалска седловина, ‘Verdikalska Sedlovina’ ver-di-'kal-ska se-dlo-vi-'na) is the flat ice-covered saddle of elevation over 750 m on Trinity Peninsula in Graham Land, [MASK], part of the ice divide between Bransfield Strait and Prince Gustav Channel.

Bransfield Strait is a body of water about 100 kilometres (60 mi) wide extending for 300 miles (500 km) in a general north-east - south-west direction between the South Shetland Islands and the [MASK] Peninsula.

Bransfield Strait is a body of water about 100 kilometres (60 mi) wide extending for 300 miles (500 km) in a general north-east - south-west direction between the South Shetland Islands and the [MASK] Peninsula.
Amadok Point (Nos Amadok 'nos a-ma-'dok) is a point on the south coast of Livingston Island, [MASK] which projects 400 m into the Bransfield Strait.
Christoff Cliff (Hristov Kamak 'hris-tov 'ka-m&k) is a rocky cliff forming Aytos Point on the coast of Bransfield Strait, eastern Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK].

Kamchiya Glacier (Lednik Kamchiya 'led-nik 'kam-chi-ya) is located on Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] situated south of the glacial divide between the Drake Passage and Bransfield Strait, and south of Tundzha Glacier, west-southwest of Pimpirev Glacier and east of Verila Glacier.

Nikopol Point (Nos Nikopol 'nos ni-'ko-pol) is a snow-free point on the south coast of Byers Peninsula, Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] projecting 650 m east-southeastwards into Bransfield Strait and linked by a spit to Vietor Rock to the south.

Pimpirev Glacier (Pimpirev Lednik pim-'pi-rev 'led-nik) on Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] is situated south of the glacial divide between the Drake Passage and Bransfield Strait, southeast of Tundzha Glacier, southwest of Saedinenie Snowfield, west of Perunika Glacier and east-northeast of Kamchiya Glacier.
Samuel Point (Nos Samuil 'nos sa-mu-'il) is on the coast of Bransfield Strait forming the southwest side of the entrance to Brunow Bay on Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK].
Vazov Point is a point on the coast of Bransfield Strait forming the northeast side of the entrance to Brunow Bay on Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK].
Aytos Point (Nos Aytos 'nos 'ay-tos) is a point on the coast of Bransfield Strait, Livingston Island, [MASK] formed by an offshoot of Christoff Cliff.

Engelhardt Ice Ridge (83°20′S146°0′W﻿ / ﻿83.333°S 146.000°W) is an ice ridge between Whillans Ice Stream and Kamb Ice Stream (formerly Ice Streams B and C) near the junction of Gould Coast and Siple Coast in Marie Byrd Land, [MASK].
Mercer Ice Stream (84°50′S145°00′W﻿ / ﻿84.833°S 145.000°W), formerly Ice Stream A, flows west to Gould Coast to the south of Whillans Ice Stream, [MASK].
Seismic waves are also generated by the Whillans Ice Stream, a large, fast-moving river of ice pouring from the West [MASK] Ice Sheet into the Ross Ice Shelf.
Van der Veen Ice Stream (83°50′S130°00′W﻿ / ﻿83.833°S 130.000°W), formerly Ice Stream B1, is a large southeastern tributary to the Whillans Ice Stream in Marie Byrd Land, [MASK].

Ishmael Peak (65°53′S62°25′W﻿ / ﻿65.883°S 62.417°W) is a conspicuous detached rock peak in eastern Voden Heights, 4 miles (6.4 km) south of Spouter Peak, which marks the north side of the mouth of Leppard Glacier, on the east coast of Graham Land, [MASK].

Marsh Spur (65°53′S62°38′W﻿ / ﻿65.883°S 62.633°W) is a spur in the eastern Voden Heights about 4.5 nautical miles (8 km) south of Bildad Peak and 4.5 nautical miles west of Scar Inlet on the east side of Graham Land, [MASK].

Leppard Glacier (65°58′S62°30′W﻿ / ﻿65.967°S 62.500°W) is a large valley glacier draining east between the Aristotle Mountains and Voden Heights, and flowing into Scar Inlet north of Ishmael Peak, on the east coast of Graham Land, [MASK].

The Gorman Crags (71°1′S65°27′E﻿ / ﻿71.017°S 65.450°E) are an east-west trending ridge marked by four craggy peaks, about 5 nautical miles (10 km) east of Husky Massif in the Prince Charles Mountains of [MASK].
Harvey Ridge is a ridge, elongated in a north–south direction, lying 2 nautical miles (4 km) east of Husky Massif in the Aramis Range of the Prince Charles Mountains, [MASK].
Mount Hicks (71°8′S64°39′E﻿ / ﻿71.133°S 64.650°E) is a ridgelike mountain with two peaks, about 12 nautical miles (22 km) southwest of Husky Massif in the Prince Charles Mountains of [MASK].

Husky Massif (71°0′S65°9′E﻿ / ﻿71.000°S 65.150°E) is a rock outcrop 2,100 metres (6,900 ft) high, about 2.5 nautical miles (5 km) long, standing 6.5 nautical miles (12 km) southwest of Mount Bewsher in the Aramis Range of the Prince Charles Mountains, [MASK].
The earlier name was amended to Husky Massif by the [MASK] Names Committee of Australia in 1970 and is considered more descriptive.

The earlier name was amended to Husky Massif by the [MASK] Names Committee of Australia in 1970 and is considered more descriptive.
Lensink Peak (71°4′S65°25′E﻿ / ﻿71.067°S 65.417°E) is the easternmost of a group of three peaks about 5 nautical miles (9 km) southeast of Husky Massif in the Prince Charles Mountains of [MASK].

Prespa Glacier (Lednik Prespa 'led-nik 'pre-spa) on Rozhen Peninsula, Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] is situated east-northeast of Tarnovo Ice Piedmont, east of the head of Charity Glacier, southeast of Ruen Icefall and southwest of Macy Glacier.

Prespa Glacier (Lednik Prespa 'led-nik 'pre-spa) on Rozhen Peninsula, Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] is situated east-northeast of Tarnovo Ice Piedmont, east of the head of Charity Glacier, southeast of Ruen Icefall and southwest of Macy Glacier.
Radomir Knoll (Radomirska Mogila 'ra-do-mir-ska mo-'gi-la) rises to approximately 300 m in Prespa Glacier, eastern Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK].

The Ruen Icefall (Ledopad Ruen le-do-'pad 'ru-en) on Rozhen Peninsula in eastern Livingston Island, South Shetland Islands in [MASK] is situated south of Huntress Glacier, northwest of Prespa Glacier and northeast of Peshtera and Charity Glaciers.

Molecule Island (66°28′S66°24′W﻿ / ﻿66.467°S 66.400°W) is the easternmost of the Bragg Islands, lying in Crystal Sound 7.5 nautical miles (14 km) north of Cape Rey, Graham Land, [MASK].

Hesperides Hill (Halm Hesperides 'h&lm he-spe-'ri-des) is a ridge linked by a saddle of elevation 52 m with the northern slopes of Atlantic Club Ridge on Hurd Peninsula, eastern Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK].

Hesperides Hill (Halm Hesperides 'h&lm he-spe-'ri-des) is a ridge linked by a saddle of elevation 52 m with the northern slopes of Atlantic Club Ridge on Hurd Peninsula, eastern Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK].

Sinemorets Hill (Halm Sinemorets 'h&lm si-ne-'mo-rets) is the second most prominent (after Hesperides Hill) in the chain of hills surmounting Bulgarian Beach in eastern Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK].

Bowling Green Plateau (79°42′S158°36′E﻿ / ﻿79.700°S 158.600°E) is a small but prominent ice-covered plateau at the north side of the Brown Hills in the Cook Mountains in Antarctica It was named by the Victoria University of Wellington [MASK] Expedition (VUWAE) (1962–63); Professor Charles C. Epsilon Island in the [MASK] is a small island lying between Alpha Island and the southern extremity of Lambda Island in the Melchior Islands, Palmer Archipelago.
Mount Dalrymple (77°56′S86°03′W﻿ / ﻿77.933°S 86.050°W) is a mountain (3,600 m) between Mount Alf and Mount Goldthwait in the northern part of the Sentinel Range, [MASK].
Mount Davis (78°06′S86°15′W﻿ / ﻿78.100°S 86.250°W) is a mountain located 1.6 km north of Mount Bentley and 2.4 km southeast of Mount Hale in the Sentinel Range, [MASK].

Mount Epperly is a 4,359 m (14,301 ft) or perhaps 4,512 m (14,803 ft) high mountain in the Sentinel Range, Ellsworth Mountains in [MASK].
Eyer Peak in Sentinel Range, [MASK] is named after Louis-Emil Eyer.

Mount Atkinson (78°39′S85°29′W﻿ / ﻿78.650°S 85.483°W) is a prominent mountain 3.5 miles (6 km) west-southwest of Mount Craddock in the Sentinel Range, [MASK].

Remington Glacier is a steep glacier about 7 nautical miles (13 km) long in Doyran Heights in the Sentinel Range of Ellsworth Mountains, [MASK].

Hammer Col is a broad ice-covered col at 3,800 metres (12,500 ft) elevation between the south part of the Vinson Massif and the Craddock Massif in the Sentinel Range of the Ellsworth Mountains, [MASK].

Gildea Glacier is a glacier 10 kilometres (6 mi) long and 5 kilometres (3 mi) wide flowing southwestward from Craddock Massif between Mount Slaughter and Mount Atkinson into Nimitz Glacier, in the Sentinel Range of the Ellsworth Mountains, [MASK].

Mount Alf (77°55′S86°07′W﻿ / ﻿77.917°S 86.117°W) is a mountain rising over 3,200 m between Mount Sharp and Mount Dalrymple in the north part of the Sentinel Range, [MASK].

Allen Peak (77°34′S86°51′W﻿ / ﻿77.567°S 86.850°W) is a 1,880-metre (6,170 ft) peak in [MASK], standing 5 nautical miles (9 km) west of Mount Wyatt Earp and forming the northern extremity of the main ridge of the Sentinel Range.

Barnes Ridge (78°8′S84°50′W﻿ / ﻿78.133°S 84.833°W) is a ridge 7 nautical miles (13 km) long, rising to over 1,210 metres (3,970 ft) (Mount Besch) and extending between Young Glacier and Ellen Glacier at the east side of the Sentinel Range, Ellsworth Mountains in [MASK].

Mount Bentley (78°07′S86°14′W﻿ / ﻿78.117°S 86.233°W) is a mountain (4,245 m) standing 2 nautical miles (3.7 km; 2.3 mi) north of Mount Anderson in the main western ridge of the Sentinel Range, [MASK].

Arapya Glacier (Bulgarian: ледник Арапя, ‘Lednik Arapya’ 'led-nik a-ra-'pya) is the 11.4 km long and 5 km wide glacier on the east side of north-central Sentinel Range in Ellsworth Mountains, [MASK], situated south of Young Glacier.

Probuda Ridge (Bulgarian: хребет Пробуда, ‘Hrebet Probuda’ 'hre-bet pro-'bu-da) is the 15 kilometres (9.3 mi) long and 4.5 kilometres (2.8 mi) wide side ridge descending from Mount Anderson north-northeastwards towards Mount Todd in north-central Sentinel Range, Ellsworth Mountains in [MASK].

Brichebor Peak (Bulgarian: връх Бричебор, ‘Vrah Brichebor’ 'vr&h 'bri-che-bor) is the peak rising to 2900 m in Vinson Massif, Sentinel Range in Ellsworth Mountains, [MASK], situated at the end of a side ridge descending southwestwards from Príncipe de Asturias Peak (4680 m).

Krusha Peak (Bulgarian: връх Круша, ‘Vrah Krusha’ 'vr&h 'kru-sha) is the peak rising to 2800 m in Owen Ridge, southern Sentinel Range in Ellsworth Mountains, [MASK], surmounting Bolgrad Glacier to the southeast and Brook Glacier to the northwest.

Bolgrad Glacier (Bulgarian: ледник Болград, ‘Lednik Bolgrad’ 'led-nik 'bol-grad) is the 7.4 km long and 5.7 km wide glacier on the west side of Owen Ridge in southern Sentinel Range in Ellsworth Mountains, [MASK], situated south of Brook Glacier and north of Sirma Glacier.

Cape Wheeler (73°58′S61°5′W﻿ / ﻿73.967°S 61.083°W) is an abrupt rock scarp rising to 460 metres, an [MASK] headland which forms the north side of the entrance to Wright Inlet on the east coast of Palmer Land.
Cape Little (74°5′S61°4′W﻿ / ﻿74.083°S 61.067°W) is a cape at the eastern extremity of the peninsula between Wright Inlet and Keller Inlet, on the east coast of Palmer Land, [MASK].

Atkinson Cliffs (71°18′S168°55′E﻿ / ﻿71.300°S 168.917°E) are high coastal cliffs, 4 miles (6 km) long, between the lower ends of Fendley Glacier and Pitkevitch Glacier on the north coast of Victoria Land, [MASK].

Brewer Peak (71°34′S168°28′E﻿ / ﻿71.567°S 168.467°E) is a peak, 2,110 metres (6,920 ft) high, along the west wall of Pitkevitch Glacier near the glacier's head, in the Admiralty Mountains, a major mountain range of Victoria Land, [MASK].

Crandall Peak (71°27′S168°41′E﻿ / ﻿71.450°S 168.683°E) is a mostly snow-covered peak, 1,840 metres (6,040 ft) high, located mid-way along the west wall of Pitkevitch Glacier in the Admiralty Mountains, a major mountain range lying in Victoria Land, [MASK].
The range trends southwest–northeast between Pitkevitch Glacier and Shipley Glacier and terminates at the north coast of Victoria Land just west of Flat Island, [MASK].
Fossils come from the Lower Jurassic of Storm Peak, [MASK].
The Kenyon Peaks (84°33′S163°36′E﻿ / ﻿84.550°S 163.600°E) are a small group of basalt peaks 3 nautical miles (6 km) northwest of Storm Peak, in the Marshall Mountains of [MASK].
Voyeykov Ice Shelf (66°20′S124°38′E﻿ / ﻿66.333°S 124.633°E), is an ice shelf fringing the coast between Paulding Bay and Cape Goodenough, [MASK].

Moscow University Ice Shelf (67°S121°E﻿ / ﻿67°S 121°E) is a narrow ice shelf, about 120 nautical miles (220 km) long, which fringes the Sabrina Coast of [MASK] between Totten Glacier and Paulding Bay.
Paulding Bay is a bay along the coast of [MASK] just west of Clark Point.
Paulding Bay is a bay along the coast of [MASK] just west of Clark Point.

Mount Athelstan (70°10′S69°16′W﻿ / ﻿70.167°S 69.267°W) is a prominent, partly ice-covered mountain, 1,615 metres (5,300 ft) high, at the north side of Trench Glacier on a spur which extends east from Douglas Range on the east coast of Alexander Island, [MASK].
Witches Cauldron (69°56′S69°49′W﻿ / ﻿69.933°S 69.817°W) is an ice-filled basin on the west side of the Douglas Range, immediately west of Mount Egbert in the north part of Alexander Island, [MASK].

Not to be confused with Mount Nichols Mount Nicholas is a mountain, 1,465 m, standing 5.5 nautical miles (10 km) south-southwest of Cape Brown and forming the northern limit of the Douglas Range on the east side of Alexander Island, [MASK].

The Dikstra Buttresses (69°48′S69°53′W﻿ / ﻿69.800°S 69.883°W) are a group of summits rising to about 1,500 metres (5,000 ft) on the western side of the Douglas Range, northern Alexander Island, [MASK].

Tumble Glacier (69°57′S69°20′W﻿ / ﻿69.950°S 69.333°W) is a glacier extending along the east side of Alexander Island, [MASK], 7 nautical miles (13 km) long and 3 nautical miles (6 km) wide, which flows east from the cliffs of Mount Egbert, Mount Ethelwulf and Mount Ethelred of the Douglas Range into the west side of the George VI Ice Shelf that occupies George VI Sound immediately south of Mount King.

Toynbee Glacier (69°35′S69°35′W﻿ / ﻿69.583°S 69.583°W) is a glacier situated in the northeast portion of Alexander Island, [MASK], extending 17 nautical miles (31 km) long and 5 nautical miles (9 km) wide, lying between Mount Huckle, Mount Spivey and Mount Stephenson of the northern portion of the Douglas Range on the west and Mount Tyrrell and Mount Tilley on the east.

Purcell Snowfield (70°29′S69°55′W﻿ / ﻿70.483°S 69.917°W) is a snowfield, 15 nautical miles (28 km) wide, lying between the east portion of the Colbert Mountains and the west side of the Douglas Range in the central part of Alexander Island, [MASK].

Mount Edred (70°35′S69°0′W﻿ / ﻿70.583°S 69.000°W) is a prominent ice-covered mountain, 2,195 metres (7,200 ft) high, which stands 10 nautical miles (19 km) inland from George VI Sound, lies about 12 miles (19 km) north of Galileo Cliffs, and marks the southern limit of the Douglas Range on Alexander Island, [MASK].

Mount Egbert (69°57′S69°37′W﻿ / ﻿69.950°S 69.617°W) is a mainly ice-covered mountain, 2,895 metres (9,500 ft) high, 8 nautical miles (15 km) south-southeast of Mount Stephenson in the Douglas Range of Alexander Island, [MASK].

Emerald Nunatak (69°39′S69°59′W﻿ / ﻿69.650°S 69.983°W) is a nunatak 1,250 metres (4,100 ft) high on the west side of the Douglas Range near the head of Hampton Glacier in northeast Alexander Island, [MASK].

Mount Ethelwulf (70°2′S69°34′W﻿ / ﻿70.033°S 69.567°W) is a mainly ice-covered mountain, 2,590 metres (8,500 ft) high, standing between Mount Egbert and Mount Ethelred at the head of Tumble Glacier, in the Douglas Range of northeast Alexander Island, [MASK].

Mount Ethelred (70°4′S69°29′W﻿ / ﻿70.067°S 69.483°W) is a mainly ice-covered mountain, 2,470 metres (8,100 ft) high, 3 nautical miles (6 km) southeast of Mount Ethelwulf and 8 nautical miles (15 km) inland from George VI Sound, in the Douglas Range of Alexander Island, [MASK].

Snick Pass (70°41′S69°25′W﻿ / ﻿70.683°S 69.417°W) is a narrow mountain pass lying between the Douglas Range and the LeMay Range, leading from Grotto Glacier to Purcell Snowfield in the central portion of Alexander Island, [MASK].

Mount Spivey (69°31′S69°50′W﻿ / ﻿69.517°S 69.833°W) is a flat-topped, mainly ice-covered mountain, rising to about 2,135 m, standing on the west side of Toynbee Glacier and 9 nautical miles (17 km) south of Mount Nicholas, situated near the northern extremity of the Douglas Range of the northeast portion of Alexander Island, [MASK].

The Douglas Range (70°0′S69°35′W﻿ / ﻿70.000°S 69.583°W) is a sharp-crested range, with peaks rising to 3,000 metres, extending 120 km (75 mi) in a northwest-southeast direction from Mount Nicholas to Mount Edred and forming a steep east escarpment of Alexander Island within the British [MASK] Territory, overlooking the north part of George VI Sound.

The Douglas Range (70°0′S69°35′W﻿ / ﻿70.000°S 69.583°W) is a sharp-crested range, with peaks rising to 3,000 metres, extending 120 km (75 mi) in a northwest-southeast direction from Mount Nicholas to Mount Edred and forming a steep east escarpment of Alexander Island within the British [MASK] Territory, overlooking the north part of George VI Sound.

It is located within the central portion of the Douglas Range, standing at the heads of Toynbee Glacier and Sedgwick Glacier 8 miles west of George VI Sound, near the east coast of Alexander Island within the British [MASK] Territory.
Mount Huckle is a mainly ice-covered mountain, 2,500 metres (8,200 ft) high, near the northern end of the Douglas Range in eastern Alexander Island, [MASK].

Shoemaker Glacier (73°47′S164°45′E﻿ / ﻿73.783°S 164.750°E) is a tributary glacier in the Southern Cross Mountains of [MASK], flowing east along the south side of Daley Hills to Aviator Glacier, in Victoria Land.
Southern Cross Mountains is the name applied to the group of [MASK] mountain ranges lying between the Mariner and Priestley Glaciers in Victoria Land.
Southern Cross Mountains is the name applied to the group of [MASK] mountain ranges lying between the Mariner and Priestley Glaciers in Victoria Land.
Hades Terrace is a steep, mainly ice-covered bluff along the east side of Campbell Glacier, situated just west of the Vulcan Hills in the Southern Cross Mountains of Victoria Land, [MASK].
The Tinker Glacier is 25 miles long glacier in [MASK], draining the central part of the Southern Cross Mountains and flowing SE into Wood Bay, on the coast of Victoria Land.

The Arrowhead Range (73°24′S164°0′E﻿ / ﻿73.400°S 164.000°E) is a mountain range 20 nautical miles (37 km) long, situated just north of Cosmonaut Glacier and west of Aviator Glacier in the Southern Cross Mountains of Victoria Land, [MASK].

The Daughtery Peaks (73°29′S164°20′E﻿ / ﻿73.483°S 164.333°E) are a small cluster of bare rock peaks 2,680 metres (8,800 ft) high that surmount the south wall of Cosmonaut Glacier in the Southern Cross Mountains of Victoria Land, [MASK].

Mount Jiracek (73°46′S163°56′E﻿ / ﻿73.767°S 163.933°E) is a mountain, 2,430 metres (7,970 ft) high, rising at the west side of the head of Tinker Glacier, in the Southern Cross Mountains of Victoria Land, [MASK].
Linn Mesa (73°32′S163°20′E﻿ / ﻿73.533°S 163.333°E) is a small mesa located 3 nautical miles (6 km) south of the Chisholm Hills in the Southern Cross Mountains of Victoria Land, [MASK].
Jacobs Nunatak (84°17′S159°38′E﻿ / ﻿84.283°S 159.633°E) is a nunatak on the west side of the MacAlpine Hills, [MASK], just west of the head of Sylwester Glacier.

MacAlpine Hills (84°13′S160°30′E﻿ / ﻿84.217°S 160.500°E) are a chain of mainly ice-free, bluff-type hills in [MASK], extending from Mount Achernar southwestwards along the south side of Law Glacier, to Sylwester Glacier.

MacAlpine Hills (84°13′S160°30′E﻿ / ﻿84.217°S 160.500°E) are a chain of mainly ice-free, bluff-type hills in [MASK], extending from Mount Achernar southwestwards along the south side of Law Glacier, to Sylwester Glacier.

The Morse Nunataks (84°16′S160°50′E﻿ / ﻿84.267°S 160.833°E) are isolated rock nunataks standing 4.5 nautical miles (8 km) south of Mount Achernar, between Lewis Cliff and the MacAlpine Hills in [MASK].

Law Glacier (84°5′S161°0′E﻿ / ﻿84.083°S 161.000°E) is a glacier about 10 nautical miles (20 km) wide between the south end of the Queen Elizabeth Range and the MacAlpine Hills, gradually descending east-northeast from the [MASK] polar plateau to Bowden Névé.

Mount Wishart (70°19′S65°15′E﻿ / ﻿70.317°S 65.250°E) is a snow-covered mountain 5 nautical miles (9 km) north of Mount Kirkby, on the north side of Scylla Glacier in the Prince Charles Mountains in [MASK], plotted from ANARE (Australian National Antarctic Research Expeditions) air photos.

Mount Wishart (70°19′S65°15′E﻿ / ﻿70.317°S 65.250°E) is a snow-covered mountain 5 nautical miles (9 km) north of Mount Kirkby, on the north side of Scylla Glacier in the Prince Charles Mountains in Antarctica, plotted from ANARE (Australian National [MASK] Research Expeditions) air photos.

Ellyard Nunatak (70°19′S64°54′E﻿ / ﻿70.317°S 64.900°E) is a nunatak on the north side of Scylla Glacier, about 7 nautical miles (13 km) south-southeast of Mount Bechervaise, in the Prince Charles Mountains of [MASK].

Foale Nunatak (70°16′S65°20′E﻿ / ﻿70.267°S 65.333°E) is a nunatak lying 4 nautical miles (7 km) east-northeast of Moore Pyramid on the north side of Scylla Glacier, in the Prince Charles Mountains of [MASK].

Moore Pyramid (70°18′S65°8′E﻿ / ﻿70.300°S 65.133°E) is a snow-covered mountain, resembling a pyramid, standing 1 nautical mile (2 km) northwest of Mount Wishart on the north side of Scylla Glacier in the Prince Charles Mountains of [MASK].
Mount Hayne (70°16′S65°2′E﻿ / ﻿70.267°S 65.033°E) is a mountain 2 nautical miles (4 km) northwest of Moore Pyramid on the north side of Scylla Glacier, in the Prince Charles Mountains of [MASK].

Arthurson Bluff (70°45′S166°5′E﻿ / ﻿70.750°S 166.083°E) is a mostly ice-covered bluff overlooking the confluence of Ludvig Glacier and Kirkby Glacier from the west, near the north coast of Victoria Land, [MASK].
Frecker Ridge (70°49′S166°13′E﻿ / ﻿70.817°S 166.217°E) is a ridge that rises abruptly along the west side of Kirkby Glacier in the Anare Mountains of Victoria Land, [MASK].

Ludvig Glacier (70°45′S166°9′E﻿ / ﻿70.750°S 166.150°E) is a tributary glacier draining north between Arthurson Bluff and Mount Gale to join Kirkby Glacier near the coast of northern Victoria Land, [MASK].
The Joubin Islands are a group of small islands lying 3 nautical miles (6 km) south-west of Cape Monaco, Anvers Island, at the south-western end of the Palmer Archipelago of [MASK].
Cape Monaco (64°43′S64°18′W﻿ / ﻿64.717°S 64.300°W) is a cape which forms the southwest tip of Anvers Island, in the Palmer Archipelago, [MASK].
Cape Monaco (64°43′S64°18′W﻿ / ﻿64.717°S 64.300°W) is a cape which forms the southwest tip of Anvers Island, in the Palmer Archipelago, [MASK].

Hugo Island (or Víctor Hugo) is an isolated ice-covered island 2 kilometres (1 nmi) long, with several rocky islets and pinnacles off its east side, located off the west side of the [MASK] Peninsula, about 74 kilometres (40 nmi) southwest of Cape Monaco, Anvers Island.
The Rosenthal Islands are a group of islands fringing the west coast of Anvers Island, 11 km (6.8 mi) north of Cape Monaco, in the Palmer Archipelago of [MASK].
Dream Island is an island lying 0.7 km (0.43 mi) south-east of Cape Monaco, off the south-west coast of Anvers Island in Wylie Bay, in the Palmer Archipelago of [MASK].

Iskar Glacier (Iskarski Lednik 'is-k&r-ski 'led-nik) is a glacier in Livingston Island, South Shetland Islands in [MASK] situated southeast of lower Huron Glacier, west-southwest of Sopot Ice Piedmont, and north of Dobrudzha and Magura Glaciers.

Paisiy Peak (Vrah Paisiy 'vr&h pa-'i-siy) rises to approximately 550 m in the Delchev Ridge, Tangra Mountains, eastern Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] surmounting Sopot Ice Piedmont to the north and east.

Pautalia Glacier (Lednik Pautaliya 'led-nik pa-u-'ta-li-ya) is a small glacier on Burgas Peninsula, Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] situated northeast of Strandzha Glacier and south of Sopot Ice Piedmont.

Petko Voyvoda Peak (Vrah Petko Voyvoda 'vr&h 'pet-ko voy-'vo-da) is a partly ice-covered peak of elevation 400 m in Delchev Ridge in Tangra Mountains, Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK], which surmounts Sopot Ice Piedmont to the northwest, and Pautalia Glacier to the east.

Ropotamo Glacier (Bulgarian: Lednik Ropotamo 'led-nik ro-po-'ta-mo) is a glacier extending 900 m in northeast-southwest direction and 600 m in northwest-southeast direction on the Burgas Peninsula, Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] and situated northeast o Dobrudzha Glacier, east-southeast of Iskar Glacier, south of Sopot Ice Piedmont and southwest of Strandzha Glacier.

Shabla Knoll (Vrah Shabla 'vr&h 'sha-bla) rises to over 400 m (1,312 ft) in Delchev Ridge, Tangra Mountains, Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] surmounting Sopot Ice Piedmont to the north and Pautalia Glacier to the southwest.

Sopot Ice Piedmont (Lednik Sopot 'led-nik 'so-pot) is situated on Burgas Peninsula, Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK], northeast of Iskar Glacier and north of Ropotamo, Strandzha and Pautalia Glaciers.

Sopot Ice Piedmont (Lednik Sopot 'led-nik 'so-pot) is situated on Burgas Peninsula, Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK], northeast of Iskar Glacier and north of Ropotamo, Strandzha and Pautalia Glaciers.

Strandzha Glacier (Lednik Strandzha 'led-nik 'stran-dzha) is located on Burgas Peninsula, eastern Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] northeast of Ropotamo Glacier, south of Sopot Ice Piedmont and southwest of Pautalia Glacier.
Besapara Hill (Halm Besapara 'h&lm be-sa-'pa-ra) is a hill of 250m projecting from Sopot Ice Piedmont in Delchev Ridge, Tangra Mountains on Livingston Island, South Shetland Islands in [MASK].
Guest Peninsula is a snow-covered peninsula about 45 miles (70 km) long between the Sulzberger Ice Shelf and Block Bay in the northwest part of Marie Byrd Land, [MASK].

The mountain was mapped by the Marie Byrd Land Traverse party, 1957–58 and named by the Advisory Committee on [MASK] Names for Paul C. Dalrymple, meteorologist, member of the wintering party at Little America V in 1957 and the South Pole Station in 1958.

Mount Lockhart (76°28′S145°6′W﻿ / ﻿76.467°S 145.100°W) is a prominent northerly projection from the main massif of the Fosdick Mountains 4 nautical miles (7 km) northeast of Mount Avers, in the Ford Ranges of Marie Byrd Land, [MASK].
Usas Escarpment (76°0′S130°0′W﻿ / ﻿76.000°S 130.000°W) is an expansive but discontinuous north-facing escarpment in Marie Byrd Land, [MASK].

The Ickes Mountains (75°29′S139°45′W﻿ / ﻿75.483°S 139.750°W) are a series of coastal mountains that extend west from Strauss Glacier for 15 miles (24 km) in Marie Byrd Land, [MASK].

Mount Isherwood (74°59′S113°43′W﻿ / ﻿74.983°S 113.717°W) is a flattish, mainly ice-covered mountain with steep rock slopes, located 4 miles (6.4 km) west-southwest of Mount Strange in the Kohler Range of Marie Byrd Land, [MASK].

Mount Jackling (77°54′S154°58′W﻿ / ﻿77.900°S 154.967°W) is a peak 1 mile (1.6 km) south of Mount Frazier in the northern group of the Rockefeller Mountains on Edward VII Peninsula in Marie Byrd Land, [MASK].

Hershey Ridge (77°40′S147°10′W﻿ / ﻿77.667°S 147.167°W) is a low, ice-covered ridge trending in a northwest–southeast direction for about 30 nautical miles (56 km) between McKinley Peak and the Haines Mountains, in the Ford Ranges of Marie Byrd Land, [MASK].
Jacoby Glacier (75°48′S132°6′W﻿ / ﻿75.800°S 132.100°W) is a steep glacier draining the eastern slopes of the Ames Range between Mount Boennighausen and Mount Andrus, in Marie Byrd Land, [MASK].

Jacobsen Head (74°2′S113°35′W﻿ / ﻿74.033°S 113.583°W) is an ice-covered headland forming the northeastly point of Slichter Foreland, Martin Peninsula, on the Walgreen Coast of Marie Byrd Land, [MASK].

Engelhardt Ice Ridge (83°20′S146°0′W﻿ / ﻿83.333°S 146.000°W) is an ice ridge between Whillans Ice Stream and Kamb Ice Stream (formerly Ice Streams B and C) near the junction of Gould Coast and Siple Coast in Marie Byrd Land, [MASK].
Hadley Point (73°55′S113°58′W﻿ / ﻿73.917°S 113.967°W) is the northeast point of Murray Foreland, Martin Peninsula, on the Bakutis Coast of Marie Byrd Land, [MASK].

Hagey Ridge (74°57′S134°56′W﻿ / ﻿74.950°S 134.933°W) is a high snow-covered ridge, between the Björnert Cliffs and Johnson Glacier, forming the east end of the McDonald Heights on the coast of Marie Byrd Land, [MASK].

Mount Aldaz (76°3′S124°25′W﻿ / ﻿76.050°S 124.417°W) is a projecting-type mountain, rising to about 2,520 metres (8,270 ft) high, that barely protrudes from the ice-covered Usas Escarpment, 22 miles (35 km) east-southeast of Mount Galla, in Marie Byrd Land, [MASK].

Maher Island is a small horseshoe-shaped island which has numerous areas of exposed rock, lying 13 kilometres (7 nmi) north of the northwest end of Siple Island, off the coast of Marie Byrd Land, [MASK].

Siple Island is a 110 km (68 mi) long snow-covered island lying east of Wrigley Gulf along the Getz Ice Shelf off Bakutis Coast of Marie Byrd Land, [MASK].

DeVicq Glacier (75°S131°W﻿ / ﻿75°S 131°W), is a large [MASK] glacier that drains the area between the Ames Range and the McCuddin Mountains in Marie Byrd Land and flows north up the entry of the Getz Ice Shelf to the southeast of Grant Island.
Van der Veen Ice Stream (83°50′S130°00′W﻿ / ﻿83.833°S 130.000°W), formerly Ice Stream B1, is a large southeastern tributary to the Whillans Ice Stream in Marie Byrd Land, [MASK].
Land Glacier (75°40′S141°45′W﻿ / ﻿75.667°S 141.750°W) is a broad, heavily crevassed glacier, about 35 nautical miles (60 km) long, descending into Land Bay in Marie Byrd Land, [MASK].

Berry Glacier (75°S134°W﻿ / ﻿75°S 134°W) is an [MASK] glacier, about 25 miles (40 km) long and 5 miles (8 km) wide, draining north between Perry Range and Demas Range into the Getz Ice Shelf on the coast of Marie Byrd Land.
Nickerson Ice Shelf (75°45′S145°00′W﻿ / ﻿75.750°S 145.000°W), is an ice shelf about 35 miles wide, lying north of Siemiatkowski Glacier and the western part of Ruppert Coast, Marie Byrd Land, [MASK].

Dean Island in the [MASK] is an ice-covered island, 37 kilometres (20 nmi) long and 19 kilometres (10 nmi) wide, lying within the Getz Ice Shelf and midway between Grant Island and Siple Island, off the coast of Marie Byrd Land.

Balchen Glacier (76°23′S145°10′W﻿ / ﻿76.383°S 145.167°W) is a crevassed glacier in [MASK], flowing west to Block Bay between the Phillips Mountains and the Fosdick Mountains in Marie Byrd Land.

Johnson Glacier (74°55′S134°45′W﻿ / ﻿74.917°S 134.750°W) is a glacier flowing north between the McDonald Heights and Bowyer Butte to merge with the Getz Ice Shelf on the coast of Marie Byrd Land, [MASK].

The Jenkins Heights (74°48′S114°20′W﻿ / ﻿74.800°S 114.333°W) are a broad ice-covered area rising over 500 metres (1,600 ft) and covering some 25 square miles (65 km2), located south of McClinton Glacier and west of Mount Bray on the Bakutis Coast of Marie Byrd Land, [MASK].

Jeffery Head (74°33′S111°54′W﻿ / ﻿74.550°S 111.900°W) is a conspicuous, rock bluff, or headland, standing 4 nautical miles (7 km) south of Brush Glacier on the west side of Bear Peninsula, on the Walgreen Coast of Marie Byrd Land, [MASK].
The Jaron Cliffs (76°23′S112°10′W﻿ / ﻿76.383°S 112.167°W) are a line of steep, snow-covered cliffs on the south side of Mount Takahe, in Marie Byrd Land, [MASK].

The longest river of [MASK], Onyx River, flows West, inland, into Lake Vanda.
