Asafiev Glacier (71°05′S70°45′W﻿ / ﻿71.083°S 70.750°W) is a glacier that flows north-west into Schubert Inlet from the western side of the Walton Mountains, Alexander Island, [MASK].
Dargomyzhsky Glacier (71°50′S70°50′W﻿ / ﻿71.833°S 70.833°W) is an outlet glacier flowing west from Duffy Peak, in the central portion of the Staccato Peaks, central Alexander Island, [MASK].
Bishop Glacier (69°42′S71°27′W﻿ / ﻿69.700°S 71.450°W) is a glacier flowing southwest into the Mozart Ice Piedmont, situated in the northwest portion of Alexander Island, [MASK].

The Ablation Point – Ganymede Heights [MASK] Specially Protected Area is a 180 km2 mountainous tract of land on the eastern side of Alexander Island in the Bellinghausen Sea, west of Palmer Land on the Antarctic Peninsula.

The Ablation Point – Ganymede Heights Antarctic Specially Protected Area is a 180 km2 mountainous tract of land on the eastern side of Alexander Island in the Bellinghausen Sea, west of Palmer Land on the [MASK] Peninsula.

Marguerite Bay or Margaret Bay is an extensive bay on the west side of the [MASK] Peninsula, which is bounded on the north by Adelaide Island and on the south by Wordie Ice Shelf, George VI Sound and Alexander Island.
It lies south west of Alexander Island and west of the base of the [MASK] Peninsula, close to the coast of Palmer Land, 48 km (30 mi) east of Smyley Island.

The Beethoven Peninsula is a deeply indented, ice-covered peninsula, 60 miles (100 km) long in a northeast-southwest direction and 60 miles (100 km) wide at its broadest part, forming the southwest part of Alexander Island, which lies off the southwestern portion of the [MASK] Peninsula.
The peninsula was first seen and photographed from the air in 1940 by the US [MASK] Service, which compiled the first rough map of southwest Alexander Island.

Latady Island is a low ice-covered island off [MASK], about 60 kilometres (35 nmi) long and more than 20 kilometres (10 nmi) wide, lying 80 kilometres (45 nmi) south of Charcot Island and west of Alexander Island.

George VI Sound or Canal Jorge VI or Canal Presidente Sarmiento or Canal Seaver or King George VI Sound or King George the Sixth Sound is a major bay/fault depression, 300 miles (483 km) long in the shape of the letter J, which skirts the east and south shores of Alexander Island, separating it from Palmer Land, in the southern portion of the [MASK] Peninsula and the English Coast.

Several glaciers also flow eastward into the sound from the east interior of Alexander Island, the vast majority of these glaciers are situated south of Planet Heights, where all of these glaciers are named after moons, satellites and planets of the solar system in association with nearby Planet Heights which was named by the United Kingdom [MASK] Place-Names Committee (UK-APC) in 1977.

The Douglas Range (70°0′S69°35′W﻿ / ﻿70.000°S 69.583°W) is a sharp-crested range, with peaks rising to 3,000 metres, extending 120 km (75 mi) in a northwest-southeast direction from Mount Nicholas to Mount Edred and forming a steep east escarpment of Alexander Island within the British [MASK] Territory, overlooking the north part of George VI Sound.
A minor embayment in this position first appeared on the charts of the US [MASK] Service, which explored the south part of Alexander Island by air and from the ground in 1940.
Ronne Entrance is a broad southwest entrance of the George VI Sound where it opens from the southeast portion of the Bellingshausen Sea at the southwest side of Alexander Island, [MASK].

Rothschild Island is an island 39 kilometres (24 mi) long, mainly ice covered but surmounted by prominent peaks of Desko Mountains in [MASK], 8 kilometres (5 mi) west of the north part of Alexander Island in the north entrance to Wilkins Sound.

In subsequent exploration by the British Graham Land Expedition (BGLE), 1934-1937, the feature was believed to be a mountain connected to Alexander Island, but its insularity was reaffirmed by the United States [MASK] Service (USAS), 1939-1941, who photographed and roughly mapped the island from the air.

Weber Inlet (71°56′S73°28′W﻿ / ﻿71.933°S 73.467°W) is a broad ice-filled inlet, which indents the south part of the Beethoven Peninsula, lying southwest of Bennett Dome, forming the northwest arm of Bach Ice Shelf in the southwest portion of Alexander Island, [MASK].

The LeMay Range (70°55′S69°20′W﻿ / ﻿70.917°S 69.333°W) is a mountain range 40 nautical miles (70 km) long with peaks rising to 2,000 metres (6,600 ft), extending in a northwest–southeast direction from Snick Pass to the north side of Uranus Glacier in the central portion of Alexander Island, [MASK].

It is located within the central portion of the Douglas Range, standing at the heads of Toynbee Glacier and Sedgwick Glacier 8 miles west of George VI Sound, near the east coast of Alexander Island within the British [MASK] Territory.
Mount Huckle is a mainly ice-covered mountain, 2,500 metres (8,200 ft) high, near the northern end of the Douglas Range in eastern Alexander Island, [MASK].
The mountain was possibly first seen in 1909 by the French [MASK] Expedition under Jean-Baptiste Charcot, but not recognized as part of Alexander Island.
It is located within the southern part of Alexander Island, west of Palmer Land in [MASK], at approximately 72°S latitude and 68°W longitude.
Mount Kliment Ohridski (Vrah Kliment Ohridski 'vr&h 'kli-ment 'o-hrid-ski) is the highest ridge (1500m) in the Sofia University Mountains on Alexander Island, [MASK].

Laubeuf Fjord is a sound in [MASK], 40 kilometres (25 miles) long in a north-south direction and averaging 16 km (10 mi) wide, lying between the east-central portion of Adelaide Island and the southern part of Arrowsmith Peninsula, Graham Land.
Hanusse Bay is a broad bay, 37 kilometres (20 nmi) long in a general north-south direction, lying between the northern portions of Adelaide Island and Arrowsmith Peninsula, [MASK].
Sheldon Glacier (67°30′S68°23′W﻿ / ﻿67.500°S 68.383°W) is a glacier flowing southeast from Mount Mangin into Ryder Bay, Adelaide Island, [MASK].
It is located in the southern approaches to Ryder Bay, Adelaide Island, [MASK], 1 mile (1.6 km) south of the Mikkelsen Islands.

The Dion Islands are a group of small islands and rocks lying in the northern part of Marguerite Bay, 11 kilometres (6 nmi) south-west of Cape Alexandra, Adelaide Island, off the west coast of the [MASK] Peninsula.
Avian Island is an island, 1.2 km (0.7 mi) long and 40 metres (130 ft) high, lying close off the south tip of Adelaide Island, [MASK].
The Ginger Islands are a group of islands lying west of Cape Alexandra, off the southern end of Adelaide Island, [MASK].
Wright Peninsula (67°28′S68°10′W﻿ / ﻿67.467°S 68.167°W) is a peninsula lying between Ryder Bay and Stonehouse Bay on the east coast of Adelaide Island, [MASK].
The Wormald Ice Piedmont (67°29′S68°5′W﻿ / ﻿67.483°S 68.083°W) is an ice piedmont covering the eastern part of Wright Peninsula, Adelaide Island, [MASK], between Rothera Point and Sighing Peak.
The Amiot Islands are two groups of islands and rocks, the Ward Islands and Cumbers Reef, respectively, lying 17 kilometres (9 nmi) west of Cape Adriasola, Adelaide Island, [MASK].

Landsat imagery taken January 1974, and named by the UK [MASK] Place-Names Committee, 1977, after Richard W. Burn, British Antarctic Survey geologist, Adelaide Island and north Alexander Island, 1975–76 and 1976–77.

Landsat imagery taken January 1974, and named by the UK Antarctic Place-Names Committee, 1977, after Richard W. Burn, British [MASK] Survey geologist, Adelaide Island and north Alexander Island, 1975–76 and 1976–77.
Cole Channel (67°22′S67°50′W﻿ / ﻿67.367°S 67.833°W) is a marine channel running north–south between Wright Peninsula, Adelaide Island, and Wyatt Island, Laubeuf Fjord, off the Loubet Coast, [MASK].

Webb Island (67°27′S67°56′W﻿ / ﻿67.450°S 67.933°W) is a rocky island in [MASK], 1.5 nautical miles (2.8 km) long, lying in Laubeuf Fjord about 3 nautical miles (6 km) south of the entrance to Stonehouse Bay, close to Adelaide Island.
Johnston Passage is a channel in [MASK], running north–south and separating the Amiot Islands from the southwestern part of Adelaide Island.
Jennings Reef is a reef, mostly submerged, extending between Avian Island and the Rocca Islands, off the south end of Adelaide Island, [MASK].
Koechlin Island is an island off the northeast coast of Adelaide Island, [MASK], about 8 kilometres (4.5 nmi) south of the Sillard Islands.
The Stokes Peaks (67°24′S68°9′W﻿ / ﻿67.400°S 68.150°W) is a group of peaks rising to about 800 m between McCallum Pass and Sighing Peak on the north side of Wright Peninsula, Adelaide Island, [MASK].
Stonehouse Bay (67°21′S68°5′W﻿ / ﻿67.350°S 68.083°W) is a bay in [MASK] on the west side of Laubeuf Fjord, indenting the east coast of Adelaide Island between Hunt Peak and Sighing Peak.

Surveyed by the British [MASK] Survey (BAS), 1975–76, they were named by the UK Antarctic Place-Names Committee in 1980 after Barry James Dikstra, a BAS geophysicist at Adelaide Island and Rothera Station, 1974–77.

Surveyed by the British Antarctic Survey (BAS), 1975–76, they were named by the UK [MASK] Place-Names Committee in 1980 after Barry James Dikstra, a BAS geophysicist at Adelaide Island and Rothera Station, 1974–77.

The Gullet is a narrow channel between the eastern extremity of Adelaide Island and the west coast of Graham Land, [MASK], separating Hansen Island and Day Island and connecting the heads of Hanusse Bay and Laubeuf Fjord.

Mount Gaudry is a mountain, 2,315 metres (7,600 ft) high, rising close southwest of Mount Barre and 5 nautical miles (9 km) north-northwest of Mount Liotard in the southern part of Adelaide Island, [MASK].
The Glover Rocks (67°46′S68°54′W﻿ / ﻿67.767°S 68.900°W) are a group of rocks lying northwest of Avian Island, off the south end of Adelaide Island, [MASK].
Mothes Point (67°14′S67°52′W﻿ / ﻿67.233°S 67.867°W) is a point 7 nautical miles (13 km) southwest of The Gullet on the east side of Adelaide Island, [MASK].

Milestone Bluff (67°38′S68°45′W﻿ / ﻿67.633°S 68.750°W) is a rock-faced, snow-backed bluff rising to about 830 metres (2,720 ft) just west-southwest of Mount Liotard, in the south part of Adelaide Island, [MASK].
Mission Rock (67°49′S68°25′W﻿ / ﻿67.817°S 68.417°W) is a low-lying rock lying southwest of the Guébriant Islands, off the south end of Adelaide Island, [MASK].

Lord Bank (67°50′S69°15′W﻿ / ﻿67.833°S 69.250°W) is a submarine bank in the Bellingshausen Sea with a least depth of 18 metres (60 ft) lying west-southwest of the entrance to Quest Channel, Adelaide Island, [MASK].

Mount Liotard (67°37′S68°34′W﻿ / ﻿67.617°S 68.567°W) is a mountain having a conspicuous ice-covered peak, 2,225 metres (7,300 ft) high, standing midway between Mount Gaudry and Mount Ditte in the south part of Adelaide Island, [MASK].
Cape Mascart (66°38′S67°41′W﻿ / ﻿66.633°S 67.683°W) is a cape forming the northern extremity of Adelaide Island, [MASK].

Hunt Peak (67°18′S68°2′W﻿ / ﻿67.300°S 68.033°W) is a triangular rock peak, 610 metres (2,000 ft) high, marking the north side of the entrance to Stonehouse Bay on the east coast of Adelaide Island, [MASK].
Hurley Glacier (67°34′S68°32′W﻿ / ﻿67.567°S 68.533°W) is a glacier between Mount Gaudry and Mount Liotard, flowing east into Ryder Bay, Adelaide Island, [MASK].

The Henkes Islands are a group of small islands and rocks 4 kilometres (2 nmi) in extent, lying 2 kilometres (1 nmi) southwest of Avian Island, close off the southern extremity of Adelaide Island, [MASK].

McCallum Pass (67°23′S68°18′W﻿ / ﻿67.383°S 68.300°W) is a pass between the northeast ridge of Mount Mangin and the ridge on the south side of Stonehouse Bay, in the southern part of Adelaide Island, [MASK].
Mount Machatschek (66°52′S68°4′W﻿ / ﻿66.867°S 68.067°W) is a prominent, mainly snow-covered mountain in northern Adelaide Island, [MASK], about 14 nautical miles (26 km) southwest of Mount Velain.
Mackay Point (67°32′S68°5′W﻿ / ﻿67.533°S 68.083°W) is a point on the southeast coast of Adelaide Island, [MASK], about 2 nautical miles (4 km) to the north-northeast of Rothera Point.
Mount Mangin is a mountain, 2,040 metres (6,700 ft) high, standing 5 nautical miles (9 km) northeast of Mount Barre on Adelaide Island, [MASK].
Horton Glacier (67°33′S68°30′W﻿ / ﻿67.550°S 68.500°W) is a glacier at the east side of Mount Barre and Mount Gaudry, flowing southeast from Adelaide Island into Ryder Bay, [MASK].
Killingbeck Island is a small island lying east of Rothera Point, off the southeast coast of Adelaide Island, [MASK].
Lagoon Island is the northernmost of the Léonie Islands, lying in the entrance to Ryder Bay on the southeast side of Adelaide Island, [MASK].
Landauer Point (67°4′S67°48′W﻿ / ﻿67.067°S 67.800°W) is a point on the east coast of Adelaide Island, marking the west side of the north entrance to Tickle Channel in Graham Land, [MASK].
Launch Rock (67°46′S68°56′W﻿ / ﻿67.767°S 68.933°W) is a submerged rock lying southwest of the Glover Rocks, off the south end of Adelaide Island, [MASK].
Rothera Point is a point at the east side of the entrance to Ryder Bay, on the south-east coast of Adelaide Island, [MASK].
League Rock (67°46′S69°4′W﻿ / ﻿67.767°S 69.067°W) is a distinctive rounded rock lying southwest of Box Reef, off the south end of Adelaide Island, [MASK].
The Léonie Islands are a group of small islands lying in the entrance to Ryder Bay along the southeast side of Adelaide Island, [MASK].

Léonie Island is the largest and westernmost of the Léonie Islands, 2 kilometres (1 nmi) in diameter and 455 metres (1,500 ft) high, lying in the entrance to Ryder Bay along the southeast side of Adelaide Island, [MASK].
Lincoln Nunatak (67°27′S68°43′W﻿ / ﻿67.450°S 68.717°W) is a snow-capped nunatak with a rocky west face, at the end of a ridge running westward from Mount Mangin on Adelaide Island, [MASK].
Limpet Island is the southernmost of the Léonie Islands, [MASK], lying in the entrance to Ryder Bay, close off the southeast coast of Adelaide Island.

Marguerite Bay or Margaret Bay is an extensive bay on the west side of the [MASK] Peninsula, which is bounded on the north by Adelaide Island and on the south by Wordie Ice Shelf, George VI Sound and Alexander Island.

Adelaide Island or Isla Adelaida or Isla Belgrano is a large, mainly ice-covered island, 139 kilometres (75 nmi) long and 37 kilometres (20 nmi) wide, lying at the north side of Marguerite Bay off the west coast of the [MASK] Peninsula.

Adelaide Island or Isla Adelaida or Isla Belgrano is a large, mainly ice-covered island, 139 kilometres (75 nmi) long and 37 kilometres (20 nmi) wide, lying at the north side of Marguerite Bay off the west coast of the [MASK] Peninsula.
Teniente Luis Carvajal Villaroel [MASK] Base is a base on the south-west tip of Adelaide Island, off the west coast of the Antarctic Peninsula.
Teniente Luis Carvajal Villaroel Antarctic Base is a base on the south-west tip of Adelaide Island, off the west coast of the [MASK] Peninsula.

Mount Lockhart (76°28′S145°6′W﻿ / ﻿76.467°S 145.100°W) is a prominent northerly projection from the main massif of the Fosdick Mountains 4 nautical miles (7 km) northeast of Mount Avers, in the Ford Ranges of Marie Byrd Land, [MASK].
Balchen Glacier (76°23′S145°10′W﻿ / ﻿76.383°S 145.167°W) is a crevassed glacier in [MASK], flowing west to Block Bay between the Phillips Mountains and the Fosdick Mountains in Marie Byrd Land.
Named by Advisory Committee on [MASK] Names (US-ACAN) for Charles D. Bitgood, geologist with the United States Antarctic Research Program (USARP) party to the Fosdick Mountains, 1967-68.
Named by Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names (US-ACAN) for Charles D. Bitgood, geologist with the United States [MASK] Research Program (USARP) party to the Fosdick Mountains, 1967-68.
Mount Ferranto is a mountain which forms the extreme southwest projection of the main massif of the Fosdick Mountains, in the Ford Ranges of Marie Byrd Land, [MASK].

Mount Getz (76°33′S145°13′W﻿ / ﻿76.550°S 145.217°W) is a mountain, 1,120 metres (3,670 ft) high, in the southern part of the Fosdick Mountains, 5 nautical miles (9 km) east-southeast of Mount Ferranto, in the Ford Ranges of Marie Byrd Land, [MASK].
Navy air photos (1959–65), and was named by the Advisory Committee on [MASK] Names for John H. Lewis, a geologist with the United States Antarctic Research Program Fosdick Mountains party, 1967–68.
Navy air photos (1959–65), and was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names for John H. Lewis, a geologist with the United States [MASK] Research Program Fosdick Mountains party, 1967–68.

The Fosdick Mountains (76°32′S144°45′W﻿ / ﻿76.533°S 144.750°W) are an east–west trending mountain range with marked serrate outlines, standing along the south side of Balchen Glacier at the head of Block Bay, in the Ford Ranges of Marie Byrd Land, [MASK].

The Fosdick Mountains (76°32′S144°45′W﻿ / ﻿76.533°S 144.750°W) are an east–west trending mountain range with marked serrate outlines, standing along the south side of Balchen Glacier at the head of Block Bay, in the Ford Ranges of Marie Byrd Land, [MASK].

Mount Richardson is a mountain just west of Reece Pass and 5 km (3.1 mi) south of Mount Colombo in the southeast part of the Fosdick Mountains, in the Ford Ranges of Marie Byrd Land, [MASK] Discovered on aerial flights from West Base of the United States Antarctic Service Expedition (USAS) (1939–41) and named for Harrison H. Richardson, meteorological observer with the biological party which visited this area in 1940.

Mount Richardson is a mountain just west of Reece Pass and 5 km (3.1 mi) south of Mount Colombo in the southeast part of the Fosdick Mountains, in the Ford Ranges of Marie Byrd Land, Antarctica Discovered on aerial flights from West Base of the United States [MASK] Service Expedition (USAS) (1939–41) and named for Harrison H. Richardson, meteorological observer with the biological party which visited this area in 1940.
Ueda Glacier (75°15′S64°35′W﻿ / ﻿75.250°S 64.583°W) is a large glacier flowing eastward along the south side of the Scaife Mountains to enter Hansen Inlet near the base of [MASK] Peninsula.

Ketchum Glacier (75°0′S63°45′W﻿ / ﻿75.000°S 63.750°W) is an eastward flowing glacier at the base of Palmer Land, [MASK], about 50 nautical miles (90 km) long, descending between the Latady Mountains and the Scaife Mountains into Gardner Inlet.
Antarctic research center on the south tip of Ross Island, which is in the New Zealand-claimed Ross Dependency on the shore of McMurdo Sound in [MASK].
Hut Point Peninsula is a long, narrow peninsula from 3 to 5 km (2 to 3 mi) wide and 24 km (15 mi) long, projecting south-west from the slopes of Mount Erebus on Ross Island, [MASK].
Cape Evans is a rocky cape on the west side of Ross Island, [MASK], forming the north side of the entrance to Erebus Bay.

Barne Glacier (77°36′S166°26′E﻿ / ﻿77.600°S 166.433°E) is a steep glacier in [MASK] which descends from the western slopes of Mount Erebus and terminates on the west side of Ross Island, between Cape Barne and Cape Evans where it forms a steep ice cliff.
The Lower Erebus Hut (LEH) is a permanent field facility located on Mount Erebus in Ross Island, [MASK].
It projects 11 kilometres (6.8 mi) into McMurdo Sound from the Ross Island coastline near Cape Evans, [MASK].
Cape Royds is a dark rock cape forming the western extremity of Ross Island, facing on McMurdo Sound, [MASK].
Mount Terror is a large shield volcano that forms the eastern part of Ross Island, [MASK].

It was named by the Advisory Committee on [MASK] Names in 1997 after James B. McClintock, Associate Professor of Biology at the University of Alabama at Birmingham, who studied the benthos of McMurdo Sound west of Ross Island and along the coast from Granite Harbour to Cape Chocolate, including extensive work in New Harbour in proximity to this point.
Island Lake is a lake lying southeast of Skua Lake at Cape Evans, Ross Island, [MASK].
Cape Crozier is the most easterly point of Ross Island in [MASK].
The Chapel of the Snows is a non-denominational Christian church located at the United States' McMurdo Station on Ross Island, [MASK].
The Helo Cliffs (77°30′S167°7′E﻿ / ﻿77.500°S 167.117°E) are a set of prominent cliffs at about 3,525 metres (11,565 ft) on the north rim of the summit caldera of Mount Erebus, on Ross Island, [MASK].
Ice Tower Ridge (77°32′S167°7′E﻿ / ﻿77.533°S 167.117°E) is a ridge at about 3,540 metres (11,600 ft) that descends the southwestern slope of the summit crater of Mount Erebus on Ross Island, [MASK].

Igloo Spur (77°33′S169°16′E﻿ / ﻿77.550°S 169.267°E) is a small, isolated spur 160 metres (520 ft) high at the culmination of the general ridge extending southeast from Bomb Peak, at the east end of Ross Island, [MASK].
Inclusion Hill (77°15′S166°26′E﻿ / ﻿77.250°S 166.433°E) is a prominent steeply conical hill, 335 metres (1,100 ft) high, between McDonald Beach and the Mount Bird icecap on Ross Island, [MASK].
Inner Crater (77°32′S167°10′E﻿ / ﻿77.533°S 167.167°E) is the topographic feature that embraces the crater within the floor of Main Crater, at the summit of Mount Erebus, Ross Island, [MASK].

The Kyle Hills (77°30′S169°2′E﻿ / ﻿77.500°S 169.033°E) are a prominent group of volcanic cones, hills, ridges, and peaks that occupy the eastern part of Ross Island, [MASK], between Mount Terror and Cape Crozier.

Post Office Hill (77°28′S169°14′E﻿ / ﻿77.467°S 169.233°E) is a prominent hill in [MASK], 430 m, standing 4 nautical miles (7 km) northwest of The Knoll and overlooking the Adelie penguin rookery of Cape Crozier, Ross Island.
Kienle Nunataks (77°28′S168°36′E﻿ / ﻿77.467°S 168.600°E) are three aligned nunataks to the north of Mount Terror in northeastern Ross Island, [MASK].
Mount McIntosh (77°31′S168°41′E﻿ / ﻿77.517°S 168.683°E) is a mountain rising to about 2,600 metres (8,500 ft) in the western part of the Kyle Hills, on Ross Island, [MASK].
The first dinosaur ever discovered in [MASK] was the ankylosaurian Antarctopelta, fossils of which were recovered from Ross Island in 1986.
Discovery Hut was built by Robert Falcon Scott during the Discovery Expedition of 1901–1904 in 1902 and is located at Hut Point on Ross Island by McMurdo Sound, [MASK].
It lives in Ross Island and Southern Victoria Land in [MASK], and on Tierra del Fuego.
Erebus Glacier (77°40′S167°6′E﻿ / ﻿77.667°S 167.100°E) is a glacier draining the lower southern slopes of Mount Erebus, Ross Island, [MASK].
The Erebus hotspot is a volcanic hotspot responsible for the high volcanic activity on Ross Island in the western Ross Sea of [MASK].

Alexander Hill (77°17′S166°25′E﻿ / ﻿77.283°S 166.417°E) is a 220-metre (720 ft) hill with a prominent seaward cliff face, lying south of Harrison Stream and Cinder Hill on the lower ice-free west slopes of Mount Bird, Ross Island, [MASK].
Algal Lake (77°38′S166°25′E﻿ / ﻿77.633°S 166.417°E) is a small, roughly circular meltwater lake about midway between Skua Lake and Island Lake on Cape Evans, Ross Island, [MASK].

It was named after Anne C. Wright (later Anne Wright-Grassham), a geologist with, firstly, the New Zealand Geological Survey field party in this area, 1977–78, then with United States [MASK] Research Program field parties, 1982–83, 1983–84, and 1985–86 seasons, with work at Ross Island, Minna Bluff, Mount Discovery, Mount Morning, and Mason Spur.
Arrival Heights are clifflike heights which extend in a north-east–south-west direction along the west side of Hut Point Peninsula, just north of Hut Point in Ross Island, [MASK].
Backdoor Bay is a small bay lying at the east side of Cape Royds, along the west side of Ross Island, [MASK].

Named by Advisory Committee on [MASK] Names (US-ACAN) for Donald A. Bierle, United States Antarctic Research Program (USARP) biologist at McMurdo Station, Hut Point Peninsula, Ross Island, 1966–67 and 1967–68.

Caughley Beach is the northernmost beach on the ice-free coast south-west of Cape Bird, Ross Island, [MASK].

Joyce Peak (77°28′S168°12′E﻿ / ﻿77.467°S 168.200°E) is a peak rising to over 1,400 metres (4,600 ft) in the northern central part of Ross Island, [MASK].

Kyle Cone (77°31′S169°16′E﻿ / ﻿77.517°S 169.267°E) is an exposed volcanic cone near Cape Crozier, located 1.2 nautical miles (2.2 km) west-northwest of the summit of The Knoll in eastern Ross Island, [MASK].
Kristin Peak (77°26′S168°19′E﻿ / ﻿77.433°S 168.317°E) is a peak rising to over 1,300 metres (4,300 ft) at the north end of Giggenbach Ridge on Ross Island, [MASK].
The Krall Crags (77°27′S166°49′E﻿ / ﻿77.450°S 166.817°E) are two rock summits rising to over 1,400 metres (4,600 ft) on the northwestern slope of Mount Erebus, Ross Island, [MASK].
The Knoll (77°31′S169°21′E﻿ / ﻿77.517°S 169.350°E) is a snow-free knoll, 370 metres (1,200 ft) high, surmounting Cape Crozier at the eastern extremity of Ross Island, [MASK].
Knob Point (77°48′S166°40′E﻿ / ﻿77.800°S 166.667°E) is a rounded coastal point on the west side of Hut Point Peninsula, Ross Island, [MASK].

Guardrail Ridge (77°32′S168°50′E﻿ / ﻿77.533°S 168.833°E) is a ridge 2 nautical miles (4 km) long located 2 nautical miles west-southwest of The Tooth in the Kyle Hills of Ross Island, [MASK].

The Hoel Mountains (72°0′S14°0′E﻿ / ﻿72.000°S 14.000°E) are a group of mountains including the Weyprecht Mountains and the Payer Mountains in Queen Maud Land, [MASK].

Kvaevefjellet Mountain (71°52′S14°27′E﻿ / ﻿71.867°S 14.450°E) is an elongated mountain, about 6 miles (10 km) long and surmounted by Mount Fučík, which has been eroded by the ice into a series of spurs that enclose small cirques, standing at the north end of the Payer Mountains in Queen Maud Land, [MASK].

Filsponen Nunatak (72°12′S14°25′E﻿ / ﻿72.200°S 14.417°E) is a nunatak rising northeast of Steinfila Nunatak in the southern part of the Payer Mountains in Queen Maud Land, [MASK].
Molchaniya Rock (72°9′S14°8′E﻿ / ﻿72.150°S 14.133°E) is an isolated rock 6 nautical miles (11 km) west-northwest of the Rokhlin Nunataks in the Payer Mountains of Queen Maud Land, [MASK].

Gårenevkalven Nunatak (72°0′S14°47′E﻿ / ﻿72.000°S 14.783°E) is a nunatak, 2,250 metres (7,380 ft) high, located 3 nautical miles (6 km) north of Gårekneet Ridge in the eastern part of the Payer Mountains, in Queen Maud Land, [MASK].

The Linnormen Hills (72°4′S14°33′E﻿ / ﻿72.067°S 14.550°E) are hills extending southwest–northeast and rising close east of Skavlhø Mountain in the Payer Mountains of Queen Maud Land, [MASK].

Mendeleyev Glacier (71°55′S14°33′E﻿ / ﻿71.917°S 14.550°E) is a glacier, 10 nautical miles (19 km) long, draining northeast through the northern outcrops of the Payer Mountains, in Queen Maud Land, [MASK].

Russian Gap (69°11′S71°13′W﻿ / ﻿69.183°S 71.217°W) is a gap extending in a north-south direction between the Havre Mountains and Rouen Mountains, in the north part of Alexander Island, [MASK].

Rosselin Glacier (69°16′S70°53′W﻿ / ﻿69.267°S 70.883°W) is a glacier flowing southwest from the southern extremity of the Rouen Mountains into Palestrina Glacier, situated in the northern portion of Alexander Island, [MASK].

Les Dents (68°57′S70°58′W﻿ / ﻿68.950°S 70.967°W) is a conspicuous landmark consisting of four toothlike peaks, uniform in height and rising to about 1,500 metres (5,000 ft) between Mount Bayonne and Mount Paris, situated within the Rouen Mountains in the northern part of Alexander Island, [MASK].

Kukri Hills (77°44′S162°42′E﻿ / ﻿77.733°S 162.700°E) is a prominent east-west trending range, about 25 nautical miles (46 km) long and over 2,000 metres (6,600 ft) high, forming the divide between Ferrar Glacier on the south and Taylor Glacier and Taylor Valley on the north, in Victoria Land, [MASK].

Gargoyle Bastion is a rocky headland rising to 60 m on the northwest coast of Varna Peninsula, Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] and forming the south side of the entrance to Hydra Cove and the northeast side of the entrance to Griffin Cove.

Hydra Cove is a small cove indenting for 200 m the northwest coast of Varna Peninsula, Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] and entered north of Gargoyle Bastion.

Aspis Island is a small, low-lying, ice-free island rising to 15 metres (49 ft), easternmost in the Dunbar group off the northwest coast of Varna Peninsula, Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK].

Dragon Beach (62°28′S60°8′W﻿ / ﻿62.467°S 60.133°W) is a broad gravel and bounder strewn area flanking Dragon Cove, and extending up to about 10 metres (33 ft) above sea level on Varna Peninsula, Livingston Island in [MASK].

Passy Peak (Vrah Passy 'vr&h pa-'si) is a peak of elevation 510 m in Vidin Heights on Varna Peninsula, Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK].

Rakovski Nunatak (Rakovski Nunatak a-'kov-ski 'nu-na-tak) is a rocky peak of elevation 430 m in Vidin Heights on Varna Peninsula, Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK].

Varna Peninsula (Poluostrov Varna po-lu-'os-trov 'var-na) is a roughly rectangular predominantly ice-covered peninsula forming the northeast extremity of Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK].

Varna Peninsula (Poluostrov Varna po-lu-'os-trov 'var-na) is a roughly rectangular predominantly ice-covered peninsula forming the northeast extremity of Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK].

Ironside Glacier is a glacier, about 30 mi (48 km) long, originating at the south side of Mount Minto in the Admiralty Mountains and draining southeast between Mount Whewell and Mount Herschel into Moubray Bay, Victoria Land, [MASK].

Mount Byrd (77°10′S144°38′W﻿ / ﻿77.167°S 144.633°W) is a mountain, 810 metres (2,660 ft) high, located 1 mile (1.6 km) north of the eastern end of Asman Ridge in the Sarnoff Mountains, Ford Ranges, Marie Byrd Land, [MASK].

The Illusion Hills (73°29′S162°20′E﻿ / ﻿73.483°S 162.333°E) are small escarpment-like hills located between the Lichen Hills and the Vantage Hills at the head of Rennick Glacier in Victoria Land, [MASK].

It was so named by the northern party of the New Zealand Geological Survey [MASK] Expedition, 1963–64, because it is visible from 50 nautical miles (90 km) north and from many points across Rennick Glacier.

Carnes Crag (71°28′S162°41′E﻿ / ﻿71.467°S 162.683°E) is a rock crag, 1,310 metres (4,300 ft) high, in the northwestern extremity of the Lanterman Range, Bowers Mountains, overlooking the junction of Sledgers Glacier and the Rennick Glacier, Victoria Land, [MASK].

Carryer Glacier is a heavily crevassed tributary glacier, 12 nautical miles (22 km) long, which drains westward from the central part of the Bowers Mountains and enters Rennick Glacier between Mount Soza and Mount Gow, Victoria Land, [MASK].

The Caudal Hills (73°10′S161°50′E﻿ / ﻿73.167°S 161.833°E) are a group of hills situated within Victoria Land, [MASK] the hills lie between the Sequence Hills and the Lichen Hills on the western margin of upper Rennick Glacier.

The Charybdis Icefalls (70°51′S161°10′E﻿ / ﻿70.850°S 161.167°E) are a large group of crevassed icefalls in the lower portion of Harlin Glacier, where it descends notably to join the Rennick Glacier at Victoria Land in [MASK].
The Freyberg Mountains (72°15′S163°45′E﻿ / ﻿72.250°S 163.750°E) are a group of mountains in Victoria Land, [MASK], bounded by Rennick Glacier, Bowers Mountains, Black Glacier, and Evans Neve.

Gressitt Glacier (71°30′S161°15′E﻿ / ﻿71.500°S 161.250°E) is a broad glacier, about 45 nautical miles (80 km) long, draining the area between the Daniels Range and the Emlen Peaks in the Usarp Mountains of Victoria Land, [MASK], and flowing northeast to enter the Rennick Glacier just north of the Morozumi Range.
Mount Gow (71°20′S162°40′E﻿ / ﻿71.333°S 162.667°E) is a mountain, 1,770 metres (5,800 ft) high, on the east side of Rennick Glacier in the Bowers Mountains of Victoria Land, [MASK].

Evans Névé (72°45′S164°30′E﻿ / ﻿72.750°S 164.500°E) is a large névé which nourishes Tucker Glacier, Mariner Glacier, Aviator Glacier, Rennick Glacier and Lillie Glacier in Victoria Land, [MASK].

The Monument Nunataks (72°35′S162°15′E﻿ / ﻿72.583°S 162.250°E) are a group of nunataks in [MASK] that have numerous pinnacles and odd-shaped projections resembling monuments, situated north of Sculpture Mountain in the upper part of Rennick Glacier.

The Morozumi Range (71°39′S161°55′E﻿ / ﻿71.650°S 161.917°E) is a spectacular mountain range of unusual scenic beauty in [MASK], extending northwest–southeast for 25 nautical miles (46 km), with its northern elevations overlooking the convergence of Gressitt Glacier and Rennick Glacier.

The Mesa Range (73°11′S162°55′E﻿ / ﻿73.183°S 162.917°E) is a range of flat-topped mesas comprising the Sheehan, Pain, Tobin and Gair Mesas, situated at the head of the Rennick Glacier in Victoria Land, [MASK].

The Litell Rocks (71°24′S162°0′E﻿ / ﻿71.400°S 162.000°E) are an area of rock outcrops within the lower Rennick Glacier, [MASK], located 5 nautical miles (9 km) east of the north end of the Morozumi Range.

Hunter Glacier (71°44′S163°0′E﻿ / ﻿71.733°S 163.000°E) is a tributary glacier, 7 nautical miles (13 km) long, draining westward from the central Lanterman Range in the Bowers Mountains of Victoria Land, [MASK] and entering Rennick Glacier at Mount Lugering.

The Usarp Mountains is a major [MASK] mountain range, lying westward of the Rennick Glacier and trending N-S for about 190 kilometres (118 mi).

The Dion Islands are a group of small islands and rocks lying in the northern part of Marguerite Bay, 11 kilometres (6 nmi) south-west of Cape Alexandra, Adelaide Island, off the west coast of the [MASK] Peninsula.

Heth Ridge is a ridge 3 nautical miles (6 km) long, located 4 nautical miles (7 km) south of the Hornblende Bluffs and near the head of Suvorov Glacier, in the Wilson Hills of [MASK].

The 500 metres (1,600 ft) long melt-water stream draining that portion of the northwestern slope of Balkan Snowfield located between Hesperides Hill, Atlantic Club Ridge, Krum Rock and Sinemorets Hill on Hurd Peninsula in eastern Livingston Island, South Shetland Islands in [MASK].

Huey Creek (77°36′S163°7′E﻿ / ﻿77.600°S 163.117°E) is a glacial meltwater stream, 1.2 nautical miles (2.2 km) long, flowing south from an ice field west of Mount Falconer to the north-central shore of Lake Fryxell, in Taylor Valley, Victoria Land, [MASK].
Canada Stream (77°37′S163°3′E﻿ / ﻿77.617°S 163.050°E) is a small meltwater stream flowing east-southeast from the front of Canada Glacier into Lake Fryxell, in Taylor Valley, Victoria Land, [MASK].

It was named by the Advisory Committee on [MASK] Names (2000) after Gary D. Clow of the United States Geological Survey, who studied sand/ice interactions and sediment deposition in perennially ice-covered lakes in Taylor Valley, 1985–86, and glacier geophysics at Taylor Dome, 1993–94 through 1995–96.

Kukri Hills (77°44′S162°42′E﻿ / ﻿77.733°S 162.700°E) is a prominent east-west trending range, about 25 nautical miles (46 km) long and over 2,000 metres (6,600 ft) high, forming the divide between Ferrar Glacier on the south and Taylor Glacier and Taylor Valley on the north, in Victoria Land, [MASK].

Canfield (after whom Canfield Mesa was named) in 1980–81, 1986–87, and 1987–88.

Ghent Ridge (77°34′S163°7′E﻿ / ﻿77.567°S 163.117°E) is a ridge that parallels the south flank of Commonwealth Glacier, 0.5 nautical miles (1 km) north of Mount Falconer, in the lower Taylor Valley of Victoria Land, [MASK].
Goldman Glacier (77°42′S162°51′E﻿ / ﻿77.700°S 162.850°E) is a glacier 2 nautical miles (4 km) east of Marr Glacier, flowing north from the Kukri Hills into Taylor Valley in Victoria Land, [MASK].

Harnish Creek (77°37′S163°14′E﻿ / ﻿77.617°S 163.233°E) is a meltwater stream, 3 nautical miles (6 km) long, that flows north from the unnamed glacier east of Crescent Glacier into the east part of Lake Fryxell, Taylor Valley, in Victoria Land, [MASK].
Harp Glacier (77°32′S163°14′E﻿ / ﻿77.533°S 163.233°E) is a tributary glacier flowing south from the glacial col west of Harp Hill into Commonwealth Glacier, Taylor Valley, in Victoria Land, [MASK].

Lost Seal Stream (77°36′S163°15′E﻿ / ﻿77.600°S 163.250°E) is a glacial meltwater stream, 1.4 nautical miles (2.6 km) long, draining from the west margin of Commonwealth Glacier into the northeast end of Lake Fryxell, in Taylor Valley, Victoria Land, [MASK].

Lizotte Creek (77°42′S162°29′E﻿ / ﻿77.700°S 162.483°E) is a meltwater stream, 2,000 metres (2,200 yd) long, flowing southeastwards from the extreme southwestern tip of Matterhorn Glacier to the northeast end of Lake Bonney in Taylor Valley, Victoria Land, [MASK].

McKay Creek (77°39′S162°45′E﻿ / ﻿77.650°S 162.750°E) is a meltwater stream, 250 metres (270 yd) long, heading on Suess Glacier west-southwest of the west end of Lake Chad at about 100 metres (330 ft) elevation and flowing east-northeast into Lake Chad in Taylor Valley, Victoria Land, [MASK].

Mount McLennan is a prominent mountain rising over 1,600 metres (5,250 ft) at the north side of Taylor Valley, surmounting the area at the heads of Canada Glacier, Commonwealth Glacier and Loftus Glacier, in Victoria Land, [MASK].

McKnight Creek (77°36′S163°17′E﻿ / ﻿77.600°S 163.283°E) is a glacial meltwater stream, 1 nautical mile (2 km) long, flowing southwest from the snout of Commonwealth Glacier and entering the east end of Lake Fryxell between Lost Seal Stream and Aiken Creek, in Taylor Valley, Victoria Land, [MASK].
Huey Gully (77°35′S163°1′E﻿ / ﻿77.583°S 163.017°E) is a high, deeply incised gully between Mount Keohane and Mount Falconer in the north wall of Taylor Valley, Victoria Land, [MASK].
Hughes Glacier (77°44′S162°28′E﻿ / ﻿77.733°S 162.467°E) is a small alpine glacier flowing toward Lake Bonney in Taylor Valley from the Kukri Hills on the south, in Victoria Land, [MASK].
Marr Glacier (77°43′S162°44′E﻿ / ﻿77.717°S 162.733°E) is a glacier 2 nautical miles (4 km) west of Goldman Glacier, flowing north from the Kukri Hills into Taylor Valley, Victoria Land, [MASK].

Henderson Hill (77°34′21″S163°11′27″E﻿ / ﻿77.57250°S 163.19083°E) is an ice free summit 0.8 nautical miles (1.5 km) northeast of Mount Falconer, rising to 700 metres (2,300 ft) on the north side of Taylor Valley in Victoria Land, [MASK].
The Matterhorn (77°40′S162°27′E﻿ / ﻿77.667°S 162.450°E) is a peak, 1,600 metres (5,200 ft) high, surmounting the north wall of Taylor Valley, [MASK], between Lacroix Glacier and Matterhorn Glacier.
The MacDonald Hills (77°33′S163°21′E﻿ / ﻿77.550°S 163.350°E) are a compact group of exposed rock hills east of Commonwealth Glacier on the north side of lower Taylor Valley, Victoria Land, [MASK].

Many Glaciers Pond (77°36′S163°19′E﻿ / ﻿77.600°S 163.317°E) is a pond, 0.3 nautical miles (0.6 km) long, located 0.5 nautical miles (1 km) south of the snout of Commonwealth Glacier in Taylor Valley, Victoria Land, [MASK].
Maria Creek (77°37′S163°3′E﻿ / ﻿77.617°S 163.050°E) is a glacial meltwater stream 0.5 nautical miles (1 km) long, which flows from the snout of Canada Glacier in Taylor Valley, Victoria Land, [MASK].

Howard Glacier (77°41′S163°5′E﻿ / ﻿77.683°S 163.083°E) is a small alpine glacier just west of Crescent Glacier, flowing into Taylor Valley on the north from the Kukri Hills, in Victoria Land, [MASK].

Mount Keohane (77°35′S163°0′E﻿ / ﻿77.583°S 163.000°E) is a peak immediately northwest of Lake Fryxell, rising to 1,250 metres (4,100 ft) between Canada Glacier and Huey Gully on the north side of Taylor Valley, in Victoria Land, [MASK].

Lyons Creek (77°44′S162°17′E﻿ / ﻿77.733°S 162.283°E) is a meltwater stream, 1,500 metres (1,600 yd) long, flowing northeast along the south side of Taylor Glacier into the west end of Lake Bonney in Taylor Valley, Victoria Land, [MASK].

Canada Glacier is a small glacier flowing south-east into the northern side of Taylor Valley in Victoria Land, [MASK].
Commonwealth Glacier is a glacier which flows in a southeasterly direction and enters the northern side of Taylor Valley immediately west of Mount Coleman, in Victoria Land, [MASK].
Lake Fryxell is a frozen lake 4.5 kilometres (2.8 mi) long, between Canada Glacier and Commonwealth Glaciers at the lower end of Taylor Valley in Victoria Land, [MASK].

The Taylor Glacier is an [MASK] glacier about 54 kilometres (34 mi) long, flowing from the plateau of Victoria Land into the western end of Taylor Valley, north of the Kukri Hills, south of the Asgard Range.

La Grange Nunataks (80°18′S27°50′W﻿ / ﻿80.300°S 27.833°W) is a scattered group of nunataks extending west for 22 nautical miles (41 km) from the mouth of Gordon Glacier, on the north side of the Shackleton Range, [MASK].
Inman Nunatak (74°49′S98°54′W﻿ / ﻿74.817°S 98.900°W) is a nunatak standing 6 miles (10 km) east of Mount Manthe in the southeastern part of the Hudson Mountains, [MASK].

Koehler Nunatak (74°52′S98°8′W﻿ / ﻿74.867°S 98.133°W) is an isolated nunatak about 20 nautical miles (40 km) east-southeast of Mount Manthe, at the southeastern margin of the Hudson Mountains, [MASK].

Mount Manthe (74°47′S99°21′W﻿ / ﻿74.783°S 99.350°W) is a mountain 575 metres (1,890 ft) high standing 5 nautical miles (9 km) north-northeast of Shepherd Dome, in the southern part of the Hudson Mountains, [MASK].

Ilarion Ridge in Breznik Heights on Greenwich Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] is named for Ilarion Makariopolski.

Schoeck Peak is a peak of 1,810 metres (5,940 ft) standing directly at the head of Henderson Glacier in the Enterprise Hills, Heritage Range in [MASK].
Soholt Peaks (79°43′S84°12′W﻿ / ﻿79.717°S 84.200°W) are a group of rugged, ice-free peaks rising between Gifford Peaks and Drake Icefall in the Heritage Range of the Ellsworth Mountains in [MASK].
Sponholz Peak (80°8′S83°0′W﻿ / ﻿80.133°S 83.000°W) is a sharp peak, 1,730 m, standing 2.5 nautical miles (4.6 km) south of Moulder Peak in Liberty Hills, Heritage Range, [MASK].
Hoinkes Peak is a sharp rock peak, 1,840 metres (6,040 ft) high, standing at the head of Henderson Glacier, where it forms part of the west wall of the glacier, in the Heritage Range, [MASK].
Holt Peak (79°45′S81°4′W﻿ / ﻿79.750°S 81.067°W) is a bare rock peak, 850 metres (2,800 ft) high, surmounting the northeast end of the Meyer Hills in the Heritage Range of [MASK].

Rhodes Bluff (79°50′S83°20′W﻿ / ﻿79.833°S 83.333°W) is a bare rock bluff 2 nautical miles (3.7 km) northwest of Mount Dolence, forming the northwest end of Enterprise Hills in the Heritage Range of [MASK].
Mount Rodger (79°42′S83°34′W﻿ / ﻿79.700°S 83.567°W) is a sharp peak, 1,410 m, at the northwest end of Collier Hills in the Heritage Range in [MASK].

Lamb Peak (79°34′S84°57′W﻿ / ﻿79.567°S 84.950°W) is a conspicuous bare rock peak located 2 nautical miles (4 km) south-southeast of Maagoe Peak in the Gifford Peaks of the Heritage Range, Ellsworth Mountains, [MASK].

Landmark Peak (79°10′S85°40′W﻿ / ﻿79.167°S 85.667°W) is a very prominent peak, 1,840 metres (6,040 ft) high, standing 5 nautical miles (9 km) south of Minnesota Glacier on the east side of Gowan Glacier, in the Heritage Range, [MASK].
Larson Valley is a relatively smooth, ice-filled valley between the south end of Inferno Ridge and Mhire Spur in the Heritage Range, [MASK].

Mount Rossman (79°47′S82°48′W﻿ / ﻿79.783°S 82.800°W) is a prominent wedge-shaped, ice-free mountain, 1,450 m, located at the north end of the Enterprise Hills between Union and Henderson Glaciers, in the Heritage Range in [MASK].
Lester Peak (79°49′S83°42′W﻿ / ﻿79.817°S 83.700°W) is a prominent snow-free peak at the south side of Hyde Glacier in the Edson Hills of the Heritage Range, [MASK].
Linder Peak (79°52′S83°12′W﻿ / ﻿79.867°S 83.200°W) is a somewhat lower but very imposing peak standing immediately south of Mount Dolence in the Heritage Range, Ellsworth Mountains, [MASK].
Kelley Peak is a peak, 1,710 metres (5,600 ft) high, forming the south end of the Liberty Hills in the Heritage Range, [MASK].

Minnesota Glacier is a broad glacier, about 40 nautical miles (70 km) long and 5 nautical miles (9 km) wide, flowing east through the Ellsworth Mountains in [MASK], separating the Sentinel Range and the Heritage Range.
The Heritage Range is a major mountain range, 160 km (99 mi) long and 48 km (30 mi) wide, situated southward of Minnesota Glacier and forming the southern half of the Ellsworth Mountains in [MASK].
The Heritage Range is a major mountain range, 160 km (99 mi) long and 48 km (30 mi) wide, situated southward of Minnesota Glacier and forming the southern half of the Ellsworth Mountains in [MASK].
Horseshoe Valley is a large ice-filled valley in the southern Heritage Range of the Ellsworth Mountains of [MASK].

The Liberty Hills (80°6′S82°58′W﻿ / ﻿80.100°S 82.967°W) are a line of rugged hills and peaks with bare rock eastern slopes, about 10 nautical miles (19 km) long, standing 7 nautical miles (13 km) northwest of the Marble Hills and forming part of the west wall of Horseshoe Valley, in the Heritage Range, Ellsworth Mountains, [MASK].
The name was applied by the Advisory Committee on [MASK] Names in association with the name Heritage Range.

Skytrain Ice Rise (79°40′S78°30′W﻿ / ﻿79.667°S 78.500°W) is a large, flattish, peninsula-like ice rise of about 50 miles extent, extending from the vicinity of Meyer Hills in the Heritage Range eastward into the Ronne Ice Shelf of [MASK].
Mount Woollard (80°33′S96°43′W﻿ / ﻿80.550°S 96.717°W) is a mountain (2,675 m) nearly 240 km (150 mi) west of the Heritage Range, Ellsworth Mountains, in [MASK].

Huron Glacier is a 7.7-kilometre (4.8 mi) long and 3.5-kilometre (2.2 mi) wide glacial flow on Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands of [MASK], situated east of Perunika Glacier, southeast of Kaliakra Glacier, south of Struma Glacier, west-northwest of Iskar Glacier and northeast of Huntress Glacier.

Sindel Point (Bulgarian: нос Синдел, ‘Nos Sindel’ 'nos 'sin-del) is a low ice-free point on the east coast of Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] projecting 250 m into Moon Bay to separate the glacier termini of Kaliakra Glacier to the north and Struma Glacier to the south.

Kaliakra Glacier (Lednik Kaliakra 'led-nik ka-li-'a-kra) is a glacier in northeastern Livingston Island, [MASK] extending 7 km in east-west direction and 8 km in north-south direction, and situated southeast of Saedinenie Snowfield, southwest of Panega Glacier, north of Struma Glacier and upper Huron Glacier, and northeast of Perunika Glacier.

Kaliakra Glacier (Lednik Kaliakra 'led-nik ka-li-'a-kra) is a glacier in northeastern Livingston Island, [MASK] extending 7 km in east-west direction and 8 km in north-south direction, and situated southeast of Saedinenie Snowfield, southwest of Panega Glacier, north of Struma Glacier and upper Huron Glacier, and northeast of Perunika Glacier.

Kaliakra Glacier (Lednik Kaliakra 'led-nik ka-li-'a-kra) is a glacier in northeastern Livingston Island, [MASK] extending 7 km in east-west direction and 8 km in north-south direction, and situated southeast of Saedinenie Snowfield, southwest of Panega Glacier, north of Struma Glacier and upper Huron Glacier, and northeast of Perunika Glacier.

Melnik Ridge (Melnishki Hrebet 'mel-nish-ki 'hre-bet) is a narrow ridge rising to 696 m in eastern Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] bounded by Kaliakra Glacier to the north and west, and Struma Glacier to the south, and linked to Bowles Ridge by the 575 m high Yankov Gap.

Omurtag Pass (Omurtagov Prohod o-mur-'ta-gov 'pro-hod) is a 720 m high pass between Mount Bowles and Ticha Peak in Bowles Ridge, Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] and is part of an overland route between the Wörner Gap area and upper Kaliakra Glacier.

Panega Glacier (Lednik Panega 'led-nik 'pa-ne-ga) on Varna Peninsula, Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] is situated southeast of the northeastern portion of Saedinenie Snowfield, south of Rose Valley Glacier, southwest of Debelt Glacier and north of lower Kaliakra Glacier.

Perunika Glacier (Lednik Perunika 'led-nik pe-ru-'ni-ka) is an 8 km long and 3 km wide (average) roughly crescent-shaped glacier in eastern Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] situated east of Pimpirev Glacier, south of Saedinenie Snowfield, southwest of Kaliakra Glacier, west of Huron Glacier, and north of Balkan Snowfield and the head of Huntress Glacier.

Saedinenie Snowfield (Lednik Saedinenie 'led-nik s&-e-di-'ne-ni-e) on Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] is situated southwest of Rose Valley Glacier, west of Panega Glacier, northwest of Kaliakra Glacier, north of lower Perunika Glacier and east-northeast of Tundzha Glacier.
Struma Glacier (Lednik Struma 'led-nik 'stru-ma) is a glacier in eastern Livingston Island in the South Shetland Islands, [MASK] situated south of lower Kaliakra Glacier and north of Huron Glacier.
Isocline Hill (83°31′S157°36′E﻿ / ﻿83.517°S 157.600°E) is a hill in the southern part of the Augen Bluffs, in the Miller Range, [MASK].
Augen Bluffs (83°30′S157°40′E﻿ / ﻿83.500°S 157.667°E) is a group of rock bluffs between Orr Peak and Isocline Hill along the west side of Marsh Glacier, in the Miller Range of [MASK].
Astro Glacier (82°54′S157°20′E﻿ / ﻿82.900°S 157.333°E) is a glacier in [MASK], between the Turner Hills and Tricorn Peak in the Miller Range, flowing northeast into the Marsh Glacier.
It was named by the New Zealand Geological Survey [MASK] Expedition (1961–62) who used this glacier to gain access to the central Miller Range.
Kreiling Mesa (83°13′S157°54′E﻿ / ﻿83.217°S 157.900°E) is a distinctive, partially ice-covered mesa at the south side of the mouth of Argosy Glacier in the Miller Range, [MASK].
Strawberry Cirque is a semi-circular glacial cirque in [MASK], 1 nautical mile (1.9 km) wide, at the south end of Macdonald Bluffs in Miller Range.
Dike Cirque (83°14′S157°57′E﻿ / ﻿83.233°S 157.950°E) is a semi-circular glacial cirque 1 nautical mile (2 km) wide in the Miller Range of [MASK].

Greene Ridge (83°12′S157°10′E﻿ / ﻿83.200°S 157.167°E) is a partially ice-covered ridge, 5 nautical miles (9 km) long, extending northward from Martin Dome to the southern edge of Argosy Glacier in the Miller Range of [MASK].
Gerard Bluffs (83°37′S157°15′E﻿ / ﻿83.617°S 157.250°E) are prominent ice-free bluffs marking the southern extremity of the Miller Range, [MASK].
Milan Ridge (83°15′S156°8′E﻿ / ﻿83.250°S 156.133°E) is a mainly ice-free ridge, 5 nautical miles (9 km) long, bordering the west side of Ascent Glacier in the Miller Range, [MASK].
Lookout Dome (83°3′S156°27′E﻿ / ﻿83.050°S 156.450°E) is an ice-covered, dome-shaped mountain, 2,470 metres (8,100 ft) high, in the Miller Range, [MASK].
Martin Dome is an elevated, snow-covered prominence between Argosy Glacier and Argo Glacier in the Miller Range, [MASK].
Hockey Cirque (83°17′S156°30′E﻿ / ﻿83.283°S 156.500°E) is a glacial cirque 0.5 nautical miles (1 km) wide along the east wall of Ascent Glacier in the Miller Range of [MASK].
The Macdonald Bluffs (83°15′S157°50′E﻿ / ﻿83.250°S 157.833°E) are prominent east-facing bluffs between Argosy Glacier and Argo Glacier in the Miller Range of [MASK], descending to Marsh Glacier.
The Miller Range (83°15′S157°00′E﻿ / ﻿83.250°S 157.000°E) is a mountain range extending south from Nimrod Glacier for 80 km (50 mi) along the western edge of the Marsh Glacier in [MASK].
The Miller Range (83°15′S157°00′E﻿ / ﻿83.250°S 157.000°E) is a mountain range extending south from Nimrod Glacier for 80 km (50 mi) along the western edge of the Marsh Glacier in [MASK].
